# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kingdom-of-kush
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] The **A-Group** was the first powerful society in Nubia, located in modern northern Sudan and southern Egypt and flourished between the First and Second Cataracts of the Nile in Lower Nubia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] It lasted from the 4th millennium BC, reached its climax at c.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Reisner first discovered artifacts belonging to the A-Group culture.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Reisner named this society the A-Group, which is now an outdated archaeological term, but remained in the literature.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Early hubs of this civilization included Kubaniyya in the north and Buhen in the south, with Aswan, Sayala, Toshka and Qustul in between.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] The A-Group population was once described as having been closely related to the pre-dynastic Egyptians as an ethnic group, although this view is considered largely outdated, with the A-Group now considered of having been related to both Sub-Saharan and North African populations.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] The A-Group maintained commercial ties with the Ancient Egyptians.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] They traded raw materials like incense, ebony and ivory, which were gathered from the southern riverine area.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] They also bartered carnelian from the Western Desert as well as gold mined from the Eastern Desert in exchange for Egyptian craft products, olive oil, and other items from the Mediterranean basin.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] A-Group dwellings consisted mostly of reed huts and rock shelters, with most settlements taking the form of temporary settlements and pastoralist communities.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] A substantial A-Group settlement is at the site of Afyeh in Lower Nubia, where the remains of houses with stone foundation slabs have also been found.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] The location, architecture, and material culture of Afyeh, along with its uniqueness in Nubia, suggest that it may have been an Egyptian (Naqadian) outpost.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] A-Group Nubians were semi-nomadic herders and rudimentary agriculturalists who also practised extensive fishing, hunting and gathering.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Evidence of agriculture first appears in the Terminal A-Group period, c.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] 3200–3000 BC (contemporary with Naqada IIIB).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Ceramic decorative motifs conserved among the A-Group and the settlement at Kadero, located northeast of Khartoum, suggests that the two groups were influenced by one another, whether directly or indirectly through trade with Egypt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Additionally, the existence of an elite group in Kadero parallels the evidence of an elite group within the A-Group.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Cemetery L at Qustul provides evidence of an elite burial, containing nearly 200 pottery vessels, some containing expensive imports from Egypt and Palestine.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] There is little evidence outside of Cemetery L to suggest social stratification of the A-Group.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] However, there is evidence that the A-Group moved from a pastoralist society to a more sedentary society by the end of the 4th millennium BC, which could suggest that the conditions were right to develop more complex social organization.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] The two main types of pottery created during the A-Group period were eggshell ceramics and black-topped red ware.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Eggshell ceramics are characterized by their eggshell-thin walls.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Black-topped red ware pottery was created by oxidizing the clay, rich in iron, creating the distinctive red color.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Subsequently, the rim was dipped in sawdust to cut off oxygen supply, creating the "black-topped" rim.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Almost all knowledge about the A-Group comes from cemeteries, as few settlements have been excavated.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Cemetery L is a royal cemetery dating back to the A-Group, and excavated by archaeologist Bruce Williams.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Cemetery L contains tombs of rulers and high officials, Cemetery V contains tombs of other officials, and Cemetery W exclusively contains burials of people with lesser status.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Excavations at Cemetery L yielded an incense burner, which was adorned with ancient Egyptian royal iconography.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Williams asserted that the royal monarchy of Egypt originated in Qustul.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] He based his reasoning on Cemetery L from three archaeological finds: the size of the tombs, their expensive contents, and royal iconography (such as pottery vessels and stone censers).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Furthermore, Williams received backlash from William Y.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Gatto argued that Bruce Williams explicitly denied making such a sweeping claim, saying that he was only trying to raise the possibility that dynastic Egypt originated near Qustul, and Nubia facilitated that process.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Gatto additionally referenced the Red Crown from the late Naqada I vessel, referenced above, claiming that Nubia almost certainly did not play a pivotal role in the rise of the Egyptian monarchy.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] While she also mentions that the tombs found in Qustul were comparable to that of Egyptian ruler's tombs, William Y.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Adams suggests that the large size and contents of their grave support a different story than the one Williams paints, relating back to social stratification.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] He states that the large tombs and their contents provide evidence for a stratified society, one that archaeologists previously had not envisioned in the A-group period.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] He claims that this evidence cannot be extended and correlated to the Egyptian monarchy.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Adams also argues that the Qustul incense burner found in the cemetery may be better suited to prove that the monarchy was situated somewhere near the Nile Valley instead of the monarchy being initially situated in Nubia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] From excavations at A-Group cemeteries, archaeologists have been tracing the genetic and ancestral lineage between A-Group Nubians and other societies.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] The specimens found in A-Group cemeteries typically had hair of a black or dark brown hue.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] On average, the men were 169.9 cm in height and the women stood around 155.5 cm.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Some individuals were wrapped in leather and positioned on reed mats.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] All of the tombs contained various burial items, including personal ornaments, utensils and ceramics.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Dental trait analysis of A-Group fossils found affinities with populations inhabiting Northeast Africa, the Nile valley, and East Africa.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Among the sampled populations, the A-Group people were nearest to the Kerma culture bearers, Kush populations in Upper Nubia, and to Ethiopians.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] In 2020, Kanya Godde analysed a series of crania which included two Egyptian (predynastic Badarian and Naqada series), a series of A-Group Nubians, and a Bronze Age series from Lachish, Palestine.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] The two pre-dynastic series had strongest affinities, followed by closeness between the Naqada and the Nubian series.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Further, the Nubian A-Group plotted nearer to the Egyptians, and the Lachish sample placed more closely to Naqada than Badari.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] According to Godde, the spatial-temporal model applied to the pattern of biological distances explains the more distant relationship of Badari to Lachish than Naqada to Lachish, as gene flow will cause populations to become more similar over time.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Overall, both Egyptian samples included were more similar to the Nubian series than to the Lachish series.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] More recent and broader studies have determined that the distinct pottery styles, differing burial practices, different grave goods and the distribution of sites all indicate that the Naqada people and the Nubian A-Group people were from different cultures.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Nubian excavations in Serra East found that the bodies buried in the A-Group cemeteries would lay on either side with their head facing south or east.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Similar to that of a curled-up position, their hands could be found near the face and their legs folded-in upwards.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Leather wrappings were also found in the burials as a means of clothing and bags.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] However, this leather wrapping was not typically found in more lavish cemeteries, such as Cemetery L at Qustul.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] As for distinct pottery styles, decorative vessels were more likely to be found in larger tombs at Qustul, whereas simpler burial arrangements contained ripple-burnished or simple vessels.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] However, the archaeological cemeteries at Qustul are no longer available for excavations since the flooding of Lake Nasser.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] According to David Wengrow, the A-Group polity of the late 4th millenninum BC is poorly understood since most of the archaeological remains are submerged underneath Lake Nasser.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Frank Yurco stated that depictions of pharonic iconography such as the royal crowns, Horus falcons and victory scenes were concentrated in the Upper Egyptian Naqada culture and A-Group Nubia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Oshiro Michinori argued, in reference to the A-Group culture, that the external influence from Nubia on the formation of Ancient Egypt in the pre-dynastic period to the dynasty period predates influence from eastern Mesopotamia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] He notes an increase in the appreciation of the contribution of Nubia in the south to Ancient Egyptian culture at the time of his writing.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] According to him, chiefs of the same cultural level as Upper Egyptian powers existed in Lower Nubia and exhibited pharaonic iconography before the unification of Egypt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] It was originally determined by Reisner that the A-Group culture came to an end around 3100 BC, when it was destroyed by the First Dynasty rulers of Egypt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Reisner originally identified a B-Group and C-Group culture that existed within Nubia following the fall of the A-Group.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] However, the B-group theory became obsolete when Henry S.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] Smith demonstrated from funerary evidence that it was an impoverished manifestation of the A-Group culture while the culture was starting to disintegrate.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/a-group-culture] With the existential crisis of the B-Group, it is suggested that these burials were simply poorer versions of A-group burials and that the span of the A-group culture lasted beyond 3100 BC.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The **Abbasid Caliphate** or **Abbasid Empire** was the third Islamic caliphate, ruled by the Abbasid dynasty.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The dynasty was descended from Muhammad's uncle, Abbas ibn Abd al-Muttalib (d.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasids rose to power in 750, when the Abbasid Revolution overthrew the preceding Umayyad Caliphate, and they ruled as caliphs from their metropole in Iraq until 1258, with Baghdad as their capital for most of their history.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasid Revolution had its origins and first successes in the easterly region of Khurasan, far from the Levantine center of Umayyad influence.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasids first centered their government in Kufa, Iraq, but in 762 the second caliph al-Mansur founded the city of Baghdad and made it the capital.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Baghdad became a center of science, culture, arts, and invention, ushering in what became known as the Golden Age of Islam.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] It hosted several key academic institutions, such as the House of Wisdom, as well as a multi-ethnic and multi-religious population, which made the city famous as a centre of learning across the world.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasid period was marked by the use of bureaucrats in government, including the vizier, as well as a growing inclusion of non-Arab Muslims in the *ummah* (Muslim community) and among the political elites.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The height of Abbasid power and prestige is traditionally associated with the reign of Harun al-Rashid (r.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] After his death, a civil war brought new divisions and was followed by significant changes to the character of the state, including the creation of a new professional army recruited mainly from Turkic slaves and the construction of a new capital, Samarra, in 836.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The 9th century also saw many provinces becoming increasingly autonomous, giving rise to local dynasties that controlled different regions of the empire, such as the Aghlabids, Tahirids, Samanids, Saffarids, and Tulunids.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] After a period of turmoil in the 860s, the caliphate regained some stability and its seat returned to Baghdad in 892.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] During the 10th century, the caliphs were reduced to mere figureheads, with real political and military power resting in the hands of the Iranian Buyids and the Seljuq Turks, who took control of Baghdad in 945 and 1055, respectively.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasids eventually regained control of Iraq during the reign of Caliph al-Muqtafi (r.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 1136–1160) and extended their rule into Iran during the reign of Caliph al-Nasir (r.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This revival ended in 1258 with the sack of Baghdad by the Mongols under Hulagu Khan and the execution of Caliph al-Musta'sim, which marked the effective end of the Abbasid Caliphate.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] A surviving branch of the Abbasid dynasty was formally reinstated in 1261 by the Mamluk sultans in Cairo, but it lacked any political power.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The dynasty continued to claim symbolic authority until the Ottoman conquest of Egypt in 1517, the last Abbasid caliph being al-Mutawakkil III.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasid caliphs descended from Abbas ibn Abd al-Muttalib, one of the youngest uncles of Muhammad and of the same Banu Hashim clan.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This family relation to Muhammad made them appealing to those who were discontented with the rule of the Umayyad caliphs (661–750), who did not descend from the same family.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Over the course of their rule, the Umayyads even suppressed several rebellions that attempted to bring other members of Muhammad's family to power.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] One of the claims that the Abbasids made in the early years of their political movement was that Abu Hashim, the son of Muhammad ibn al-Hanafiyya and grandson of Ali, had formally transferred the Imamate (*imāmah*) to Muhammad ibn Ali (the great-grandson of Abbas) and thus to the Abbasid family.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Muhammad ibn Ali began to campaign in Persia for the return of power to the family of Muhammad, the Hashemites, in the context of the reign of Umar II.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Later, after they had attained power and needed to broaden their support among Muslims, the Abbasids supplemented this claim with other claims to justify their legitimacy.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasids also distinguished themselves from the Umayyads by attacking their moral character and administration in general.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasids also appealed to non-Arab Muslims, known as *mawali*, who remained outside the kinship-based society of the Arabs and were perceived as a lower class within the Umayyad empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] According to Ira Lapidus, "The Abbasid revolt was supported largely by Arabs, mainly the aggrieved settlers of Merv with the addition of the Yemeni faction and their Mawali".
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] During the reign of Marwan II, this opposition culminated in the rebellion of Ibrahim al-Imam, the fourth in descent from Abbas.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Supported by the province of Khurasan (eastern Iran), even though the governor opposed them, and the Shi'i Arabs, he achieved considerable success, but was captured and died in prison in 749.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] On 9 June 747 (15 Ramadan AH 129), Abu Muslim, rising from Khurasan, successfully initiated an open revolt against Umayyad rule, which was carried out under the sign of the Black Standard.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Close to 10,000 soldiers were under Abu Muslim's command when the hostilities officially began in Merv.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] General Qahtaba followed the fleeing governor Nasr ibn Sayyar west defeating the Umayyads at the Battle of Gorgan, the Battle of Nahavand and finally in the Battle of Karbala, all in the year 748.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Ibrahim was captured by Marwan and was killed.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The quarrel was taken up by Ibrahim's brother Abdallah, known by the name of Abu al-'Abbas al-Saffah, who defeated the Umayyads in 750 in the battle near the Great Zab river and was subsequently proclaimed caliph.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] After this loss, Marwan fled to Egypt, where he was subsequently killed.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The remainder of his family, barring one male, were also eliminated.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 750–754) was spent consolidating Abbasid rule over the Muslim community.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Soon after the victory of 750, Abu Muslim sent forces to Central Asia to confront an army from Tang China led by Gao Xianzhi.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Gao Xianzhi and his army were defeated in 751 at the Battle of Talas, near present-day Tashkent, by the Abbasid army under Ziyad ibn Salih.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This defeat marked the end of Tang influence in Transoxiana and halted Tang westward expansion.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasids then consolidated their rule in Transoxania.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Elsewhere, the Abbasids focused on putting down numerous rebellions in Syria and Iraq.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Byzantines conducted raids during these early distractions.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] One of the first major changes effected by Abbasid rule was the move of the caliphate's center of power from Syria to Iraq.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This was closer to the Persian *mawali* support base of the Abbasids and the move addressed their demand for reduced Arab dominance in the empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] However, no definitive capital was yet selected.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In these early Abbasid years, Kufa generally served as the administrative capital, but the caliphs were wary of the Alid sympathies in the city and did not always reside here.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 752, al-Saffah built a new city called al-Hashimiyya, at an uncertain location, most likely near Kufa.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Later that same year, he moved to Anbar, where he built a new settlement for his Khurasani soldiers and a palace for himself.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] It was al-Saffah's successor, Abu Ja'far al-Mansur (r.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 754–775) who firmly consolidated Abbasid rule and faced down internal challenges.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] His uncle, Abdallah ibn Ali, the victor over the Umayyads at the Battle of the Zab, was the most serious potential rival for leadership and al-Mansur sent Abu Muslim, the Khurasani revolutionary commander, against him in 754.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] After Abu Muslim successfully defeated him, al-Mansur then turned to eliminate Abu Muslim himself.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] He arranged to have him arrested and executed in 755.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] On the western frontier, the Abbasids were unable to re-assert caliphal control over the western and central Maghreb, which the Umayyads had lost in the 740s.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] One member of the Umayyad dynasty, Abd ar-Rahman, also managed to escape the purge of his family and established independent rule in al-Andalus (present-day Spain and Portugal) in 756, founding the Umayyad emirate of Córdoba.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 756, al-Mansur had also sent over 4,000 Arab mercenaries to assist the Tang dynasty against the rebel leader An Lushan.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasids, or "Black Flags" as they were commonly called, were known in Tang dynasty chronicles as the *hēiyī Dàshí*, "The Black-robed Tazi" (黑衣大食) ("Tazi" being a borrowing from Persian *Tāzī*, the word for "Arab").
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Later, Caliph Harun al-Rashid sent embassies to China and established good relations with the Tang emperors.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] After the war, these embassies remained in China and al-Rashid established an alliance with China.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Several embassies from the Abbasid caliphs to the Chinese court have been recorded in the *Old Book of Tang*, the most important being those of al-Saffah, al-Mansur, and Harun al-Rashid.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 762, al-Mansur suppressed a rebellion in the Hejaz led by al-Nafs al-Zakiyya, a descendant from Ali ibn Abi Talib, whose challenge to the Abbasid claim to leadership was based on his Alid lineage and thus presented a serious political threat.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] He was defeated by an Abbasid army led by Isa ibn Musa.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] It was after this victory, in 762, that al-Mansur finally established a proper Abbasid capital, Baghdad – officially called *Madinat al-Salam* ('City of Peace') – located on the Tigris River, near the former ancient capital city of Ctesiphon.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Prior to this, he had continued to consider multiple sites for a capital, including al-Hashimiyya, which he used as a capital for a while, and al-Rumiyya (near the ruins of Ctesiphon), which he used for a few months.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Various other sites in the region also appear to have served as "capitals" under either al-Saffah or al-Mansur prior to the founding of Baghdad.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Mansur centralised the judicial administration and, later, Harun al-Rashid established the institution of Great Qadi to oversee it.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Umayyad empire was mostly Arab; however, the Abbasids progressively became made up of more and more converted Muslims in which the Arabs were only one of many ethnicities.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasids had depended heavily on the support of Persians in their overthrow of the Umayyads.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Mansur welcomed non-Arab Muslims to his court.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] While this helped integrate Arab and Persian cultures, it alienated many of their Arab supporters, particularly the Khurasani Arabs who had supported them in their battles against the Umayyads.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] It was also during this early period of the dynasty, in particular during the rule of al-Mansur, Harun al-Rashid, and al-Ma'mun, that its reputation and power were created.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The position of *wazir* (vizier) developed in this period.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] It was initially akin to a secretary, but under the tenure of the Barmakids, an Iranian family close to the Abbasids, the position became powerful and Harun al-Rashid delegated state affairs to them for many years.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This resulted in a more ceremonial role for many Abbasid caliphs compared with caliphal rule under the Umayyads; the viziers began to exert greater influence, and the role of the caliph's aristocracy was slowly replaced by a Barmakid bureaucracy.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] At the western end of the empire, Harun al-Rashid agreed to grant the province of Ifriqiya (centered in present-day Tunisia) as a hereditary emirate to Ibrahim ibn al-Aghlab, who founded the Aghlabid dynasty there.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 786–809), the Abbasid Empire reached its peak.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 775–785), restarted the fighting with the Byzantines, and his sons continued the conflict until Empress Irene pushed for peace.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] After several years of peace, Nikephoros I broke the treaty, then fended off multiple incursions during the first decade of the 9th century.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] These Abbasid attacks pushed into the Taurus Mountains, culminating with a victory at the Battle of Krasos and the massive invasion of 806, led by al-Rashid himself.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Harun al-Rashid's navy also proved successful, taking Cyprus.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Rashid then focused on the rebellion of Rafi ibn al-Layth in Khurasan and died while there.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Domestically, al-Rashid pursued policies similar to those of his father al-Mahdi.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] He released many of the Umayyads and Alids his brother al-Hadi (r.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 785–786) had imprisoned and declared amnesty for all political groups of the Quraysh.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] While Baghdad remained the official capital, al-Rashid chose to reside in Raqqa from 796 until the end of his reign.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 802, he established an unusual succession plan which decreed that his son al-Amin would inherit the title of Caliph and have control of Iraq and the western empire while his other son al-Ma'mun would rule Khurasan and most eastern parts of the empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 803, he turned on and imprisoned or killed most of the Barmakids, who had wielded administrative power on his behalf.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The reasons for this sudden and ruthless move remain unclear and have been the subject of much discussion by contemporary writers and later historians.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Rashid's decision to split the succession proved to be damaging to the longevity of the empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] After his death in 809, his succession pact eventually collapsed and the empire was split by a civil war between al-Amin in Iraq and al-Ma'mun in Khurasan.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This ended with a successful siege of Baghdad by al-Ma'mun's forces.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] When the city fell in 813, al-Amin was captured and executed on the orders of al-Ma'mun's general, Tahir ibn Husayn.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This marked the first time that an Abbasid ruler was publicly executed and it irrevocably damaged the prestige of the caliphate.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Ma'mun became caliph and ruled until his death in 833.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] He initially ruled the empire from his established base in Merv, Khurasan, where his main support was found, but this prolonged the discontent and instability in Iraq and triggered further fighting in the years following his victory.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 817, he officially declared an Alid, 'Ali al-Rida, as his heir, instead of an Abbasid family member, perhaps hoping to promote Muslim unity, but the move backfired.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Eventually, he was compelled to step back from these policies and move his court to Baghdad, where he arrived in August 819.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] After this, the rest of his reign was relatively peaceful.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Exceptions included a rebellion in Azerbaijan by the Khurramites, supported by the Byzantines, which continued until 837.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] He also repulsed a Byzantine attack on Syria around 829, followed by counter-attacks into Anatolia, and suppressed a rebellion in Egypt in 832.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The later years of al-Ma'mun's reign are known for his intellectual interests and patronage.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The so-called "translation movement" — the state-sponsored translation of scientific and literary works of antiquity into Arabic — that had begun under his predecessors was pushed even further during this time and al-Ma'mun shifted its focus to ancient Greek works of science and philosophy.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In matters of religion, his interest in philosophy spurred him to endorse Mu'tazilism, the rationalist school of Islamic thought.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Under its influence, he officially endorsed the doctrine of createdness of the Qur'an in 827.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 833, he went further and forcibly imposed it on the *ulama*, the Sunni religious scholars.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This controversial policy, known as the *Mihna*, was eventually abandoned in 848.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Ultimately, it failed to convince the Sunni *ulama* and instead contributed to the emergence of the latter as a more cohesive social class whose views and interests did not always align with the caliph.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Following the civil war between al-Amin and al-Ma'mun, the traditional mainstay of the Abbasid army, the *Khurasaniyya* and *'Abna al-dawla*, were no longer seen as reliable and the caliphs sought to recruit a new type of army whose loyalty could be better assured.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This process began under al-Ma'mun but it is his brother and successor, al-Mu'tasim (r.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 833–842), who is known for its more radical implementation.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Soldiers were recruited from several new sources, but the most important, especially under al-Mu'tasim, were the group referred to by Arabic chronicles as "Turks" (*atrāk*), who appear to have been mainly Turkic people from Central Asia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Some modern scholars refer to them as Mamluks, marking them as the antecedent of the later slave-soldiers known by that term, but their exact legal status has been a subject of scholarly debate.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Many, perhaps the majority, were originally purchased or captured slaves, but they were paid regular salaries and thus likely manumitted.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In any case, these outsiders did not have political ties among the traditional elites and thus their loyalty was to the caliph alone.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] These troops were likely the first standing army of the caliphate and provided the caliph with a strong base of military support.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] However, the influx of new foreign troops into the capital created tensions with its inhabitants and with older elites.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This was one of the main reasons why, in 836, al-Mu'tasim decided to found a new capital, Samarra, on an open site to the north of Baghdad.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The new capital housed the caliph's army, allowed for the unhindered construction of massive new palaces, and became the focus of an even more elaborate courtly culture.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Mu'tasim's reign marked the end of the strong caliphs.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] He strengthened his personal army with the Mamluks and promptly restarted the war with the Byzantines.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Though his attempt to seize Constantinople failed when his fleet was destroyed by a storm, his military excursions were generally successful, culminating with a resounding victory in the Sack of Amorium.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] From the ninth century onward, the Abbasids found they could no longer keep together a centralized polity from Baghdad, which had grown larger than that of Rome.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] As mentioned, Harun al-Rashid had already granted the province of Ifriqiya to the Aghlabids, who ruled this region as an autonomous vassal state until its fall to the Fatimids in 909.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In al-Ma'mun's reign, Tahir ibn Husayn (al-Ma'mun's general in the civil war) was appointed viceroy of Iran and most of the eastern regions of the empire from 821 onward.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] His descendants, the Tahirids, continued to govern in this position with significant autonomy until 873, although they remained loyal to the caliph and used only the title of *amir*.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] From their capital at Nishapur, they were important patrons of Arabic literature and Sunni religious scholarship, in addition to making major improvements to agriculture.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In Transoxiana, the Persian Samanids of Bukhara and Samarkand ruled as local governors, initially under the Tahirids.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] They oversaw the development of the region's cities into major trade centers, profiting from long-distance trade between China, Central Asia, Eastern Europe, and the Middle East.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 847–861) was characterized by the caliph's extravagant spending, his attempts to further consolidate power within the state, and his replacement of the *Mihna* policy with support for more orthodox Sunni scholars, in particular the Hanbali school.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 853, the Byzantines sacked Damietta in Egypt, and the caliph responded by sending troops into Anatolia, who sacked and marauded until they were eventually annihilated in 863.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Mutawakkil's lifestyle and spending weakened his support among the military.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 861, he was murdered at a party by a group of Turkish soldiers.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This was the first time the Abbasid military intervened so directly and violently at court and it set a precedent for further coups.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The following period, sometimes known as the "Anarchy at Samarra" (861–870), saw four different caliphs come and go.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] While they each attempted to reassert their authority, they were at the mercy of military and political factions.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Tax collection lapsed and, along with al-Mutawakkil's previous spending, this left the state short on funds, which exacerbated the infighting.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 865, the Turkish soldiers of Samarra even besieged Baghdad to overthrow the caliph al-Musta'in and, when the city fell the following year, they replaced him with al-Mu'tazz.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The latter was overthrown by the same faction in 869 and replaced by al-Muhtadi, who was similarly overthrown in 870.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Muhtadi was succeeded by al-Mu'tamid, who was finally able to restore some order, in large part thanks to the help of his brother al-Muwaffaq, who kept the military under control and ran most government affairs.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The restoration was hampered by the Zanj rebellion, which erupted in 869 and threatened the center of Abbasid control in Iraq.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This major threat was not brought under control until a determined campaign was launched in 879.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] By the 870s, Egypt became autonomous under Ahmad ibn Tulun and his Tulunid successors, though they continued to acknowledge the caliph and generally sent tribute to Baghdad.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] For a time, they even controlled Syria and parts of the Jazira (Upper Mesopotamia).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 882, the caliph al-Mu'tamid even tried to move his residence to Egypt at Ibn Tulun's invitation, though this move was aborted by the intervention of al-Muwaffaq.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In the east, the Saffarids were former soldiers in the Abbasid army who were stationed in Sistan and remained there as local strongmen.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] They began to challenge the Tahirids from 854 onward and in 873 they captured Nishapur, ending Tahirid rule.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] They marched on Baghdad in 876 but were defeated by al-Muwaffaq.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The two sides were forced to come to terms and the Abbasids allowed the Saffarids to rule over Sistan, Fars, Kirman, and Khurasan.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 898, al-Mu'tadid set the Saffarids and Samanids against each other by formally endorsing a Saffarid claim over Transoxiana, the Samanid domain.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Samanids emerged triumphant in battle and were able to expand their control thenceforth to Khurasan, while the Saffarids were contained further south.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Samanids never threatened Iraq or western Iran, but they were also not as close to the caliphs as their Tahirid predecessors and in practice they were almost entirely independent of Baghdad.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] They became even greater patrons of religion and the arts than the Tahirids.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] They still maintained an orthodox Sunni ideology but they differed from their predecessors by promoting the Persian language.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] There was a brief Abbasid political and military revival at the end of the 9th century, especially under the policies of caliphs al-Mu'tadid (r.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Under al-Mu'tadid, the capital was moved from Samarra back to Baghdad.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Incursions by the Qarmatians and allied Bedouin tribes posed a serious threat from 899 onwards, but the Abbasid army, led by Muhammad ibn Sulayman, won a reprieve against them in 904 and 907.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 905, the same general invaded Egypt and overthrew the weakened Tulunids, re-establishing Abbasid control to the west.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] By the time caliph al-Muktafi died in 908, the Abbasid revival was at its peak and a strong centralized state was in place again.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] After his death, however, the state became dominated by feuding bureaucrats.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 908–932), the Abbasid court continued to project power and wealth publicly but the politics and financial policies of the time compromised the caliphate's sustainability in the long-term.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] It was in this period that the practice of giving out *iqta*s (fiefs in the form of tax farms) as favours began, which had the effect of reducing the caliphate's own tax revenues.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 909, North Africa was lost to the Fatimid dynasty, an Isma'ili Shia sect tracing its roots to Muhammad's daughter Fatima.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Fatimids took control of Ifriqiya from the Aghlabids and eventually conquered Egypt in 969, where they established their capital, Cairo, near Fustat.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] By the end of the century, they were one of the main political and ideological challenges to Sunni Islam and the Abbasids, contesting the Abbasids for the titular authority of the Islamic *ummah*.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The challenge of the Fatimid Caliphate only ended with their downfall in the 12th century.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 934–941), Baghdad's authority declined further as local governors refused to send payments to the capital.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Ikhshidids ruled Egypt and Syria autonomously prior to the Fatimid takeover.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Even in Iraq, many governors refused to obey and the caliph was unable to send armies against them.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Radi was forced to invite the governor of Wasit, Muhammad ibn Ra'iq, to take over the administration under the newly created position of *amir al-umara* ("Commander of Commanders").
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Ibn Ra'iq disbanded the salaried army of the caliph and reduced much of the government's bureaucratic infrastructure, including the traditional vizierate, thus removing much of the Abbasid state's basis for power.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] He was overthrown in 938 and the following years were bogged down in political turmoil.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Mustakfi had a short reign from 944 to 946, and it was during this period that the Persian faction known as the Buyids from Daylam swept into power and assumed control over the bureaucracy in Baghdad.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] According to the history of Miskawayh, they began distributing *iqta*s to their supporters.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This period of localized secular control was to last nearly 100 years.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Mahmud of Ghazni took the title of sultan, as opposed to the *amir* that had been in more common usage, signifying the Ghaznavid Empire's independence from caliphal authority, despite Mahmud's ostentatious displays of Sunni orthodoxy and ritual submission to the caliph.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In the 11th century, the loss of respect for the caliphs continued, as some Islamic rulers no longer mentioned the caliph's name in the Friday *khutba*, or struck it off their coinage.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Despite the power of the Buyid amirs, the Abbasids retained a highly ritualized court in Baghdad, as described by the Buyid bureaucrat Hilal al-Sabi', and they retained a certain influence over Baghdad as well as religious life.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] As Buyid power waned with the rule of Baha' al-Daula, the caliphate was able to regain some measure of strength.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The caliph al-Qadir, for example, led the ideological struggle against the Shia with writings such as the *Baghdad Manifesto*.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The caliphs kept order in Baghdad itself, attempting to prevent the outbreak of *fitna*s in the capital, often contending with the *ayyarun*.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] With the Buyid dynasty on the wane, a vacuum was created that was eventually filled by the dynasty of Oghuz Turks known as the Seljuqs.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] By 1055, the Seljuqs had wrested control from the Buyids and Abbasids, and took temporal power.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] When the amir and former slave Basasiri took up the Shia Fatimid banner in Baghdad in 1056–57, the caliph al-Qa'im was unable to defeat him without outside help.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Toghril Beg, the Seljuq sultan, restored Baghdad to Sunni rule and took Iraq for his dynasty.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Once again, the Abbasids were forced to deal with a military power that they could not match, though the Abbasid caliph remained the titular head of the Islamic community.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The succeeding sultans Alp Arslan and Malikshah, as well as their vizier Nizam al-Mulk, took up residence in Persia, but held power over the Abbasids in Baghdad.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] When the dynasty began to weaken in the 12th century, the Abbasids gained greater independence once again.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 1118–1135) was the first caliph to build an army and to lead it in battle since the 10th century.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] He recruited Kurdish and Arab Bedouin tribes and re-fortified Baghdad.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] His first concern was not the Seljuks but the Mazyadids of Hilla in central Iraq, whom he met in battle in 1123.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] His bid for independence was ultimately unsuccessful, as he was defeated by a Seljuk army in 1135 and assassinated soon after.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 1136–1160), a new caliphal state began to emerge with the help of his vizier Ibn Hubayra.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Ibn Hubayra concentrated on reasserting authority in Iraq while the Seljuk Empire deteriorated.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasids successfully defended Baghdad against the Seljuqs in the siege of 1157 and then conquered their Mazyadid enemies in Hilla in 1162.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] By the end of al-Muqtafi's reign, Baghdad controlled a state stretching from Basra in the south to the edges of Mosul in the north.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] After over two hundred years of Abbasid subjection to foreign dynasties, Caliph al-Mustanjid (r.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 1160–1170) formally declared independence from the Seljuk sultans in 1165, when he dropped their names from Abbasid coinage.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Initially, the caliphs were still vulnerable to the power of the viziers, but al-Mustadi (r.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 1170–1180) was able to further rally some support from the Baghdad public as well as symbolic support abroad from the Ayyubid sultan Saladin and the Rum Seljuk sultan Kilij Arslan II.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 1180–1225) marked a definitive shift in late Abbasid power.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] He reinvigorated public displays of caliphal prestige, removed officials who were too powerful, engaged in diplomacy with regions beyond Iraq, and extended his control over former Seljuk territories in western Iran — including Isfahan, Hamadan, Qazvin and Zanjan.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] He sought to build up his influence among Muslim rulers abroad largely through the Sufi-inspired *futuwwa* brotherhood that he headed.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] 1226–1242), the Abbasid state achieved significant stability and many of the same policies continued.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] He built the Mustansiriyya Madrasa, inaugurated in 1234, the first madrasa to teach all four Sunni *maddhab*s (schools of jurisprudence) and the first madrasa commissioned by an Abbasid caliph.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 1206, Genghis Khan established a powerful dynasty among the Mongols of Central Asia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] During the 13th century, this Mongol Empire conquered most of the Eurasian land mass, including both China in the east and much of the old Islamic caliphate and the Kievan Rus' in the west.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 1252, Hulagu Khan, a grandson of Genghis Khan and brother of the new Mongol ruler, Möngke Khan, was placed in charge of a new western campaign to the Middle East that would culminate in the conquest of Baghdad in 1258.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In the years leading up the Mongol invasion, Baghdad's strength was sapped by political rivalries, sectarian tensions between Sunnis and Shias, and damaging floods.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 1257, after destroying the Assassins in Iran, Hulagu wrote to the Abbasid caliph, al-Musta'sim, demanding his submission.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The caliph refused, with Hulagu's status as a non-Muslim (unlike the earlier Buyids and Seljuks) likely a factor.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] There followed months of diplomacy, during which the Mongols may have been informed of Baghdad's weakness by correspondence with the caliph's vizier, Ibn al-Alqami, a Shia who was later accused of colluding with them.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Mongols began their siege of the city on 29 January 1258.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] On 10 February, al-Musta'sim agreed to meet with Hulagu, who demanded that the caliph order the defenders to stand down and come out of the city in exchange for mercy.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The caliph complied, but the Mongols slaughtered the population and then began the sack of the city on 13 February.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Contemporary accounts describe destruction, looting, rape, and killing on a massive scale over many days, with hundreds of thousands killed and the city reduced to near-empty ruins, though some, like the Christian and Shia communities, were spared.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Mongols feared rumours that a supernatural disaster would strike if the blood of al-Musta'sim, a direct descendant of Muhammad's uncle and part of a dynasty that had reigned for five centuries, was spilled.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] As a precaution and in accordance with a Mongol taboo against spilling royal blood, Hulagu had al-Musta'sim wrapped in a carpet and trampled to death by horses on 20 February 1258.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The caliph's immediate family was also executed, with the lone exceptions of his youngest son who was sent to Mongolia and a daughter who became a slave in the harem of Hulagu.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The fall of Baghdad marked the effective end of the Abbasid Caliphate.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] It made a deep impression on contemporary and later writers both inside and outside the Muslim world, some of whom created legendary stories about the last caliph's demise.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] It is also traditionally seen as the approximate end to the "classical age" or "golden age" of Islamic civilization.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The events brought profound geopolitical changes to the traditional lands of the Islamic caliphate, with Iraq, Iran, and most of the eastern lands falling under Mongol control while other Muslim rulers retained the lands to the west.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Mongol expansion further west was eventually halted by the Mamluks of Egypt at the Battle of Ain Jalut in 1260, followed by the conflict between the Ilkhanids (Hulagu and his successors) and their Golden Horde rivals, which diverted Mongol attention.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Prior to the Mongol invasion, the later Ayyubid sultans of Egypt had built up an army recruited from slaves, the Mamluks.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] During a political and military crisis in 1250, the Mamluks seized power and established what is now known as the Mamluk Sultanate.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Following the devastation of Baghdad in 1258 and in an effort to secure political legitimacy for the new regime in Egypt, the Mamluk ruler Baybars invited a surviving member of the Abbasid family to establish himself in Cairo in 1260–1261.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The new caliph was al-Mustansir II, a brother of the former caliph al-Mustansir.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 1262, he disappeared while leading a small army in an attempt to recapture Baghdad from the Mongols.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Baybars subsequently replaced him with al-Hakim I, another Abbasid family member who had just been proclaimed in Aleppo.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Thereafter, the Abbasid caliphs in Cairo continued to exist as a strictly ceremonial but nonetheless important institution within the Mamluk Sultanate, conferring significant prestige on the Mamluks.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] It continued to be relevant even to other Muslim rulers until the 14th century; for example, the sultans of Delhi, the Muzaffarid sultan Muhammad, the Jalayirid sultan Ahmad, and the Ottoman sultan Bayezid I all sought diplomas of investiture from the caliph or declared nominal allegiance to him.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Caliph al-Musta'in even managed to reign as sultan in Cairo for a brief six months in 1412.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] During the 15th century, however, the institution of the caliph declined in significance.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The last Abbasid caliph in Cairo was al-Mutawakkil III, who was in place when the Ottoman sultan Selim I defeated the Mamluks in 1516 and conquered Egypt in 1517, ending the Mamluk Sultanate.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Selim I met with al-Mutawakkil III in Aleppo in 1516, prior to marching into Egypt, and the caliph was then sent to the Ottoman capital of Constantinople (present-day Istanbul), ending the Abbasid caliphate definitively.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasids themselves slipped into historical obscurity after this.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The idea of a "caliphate" subsequently became an ambiguous concept that was occasionally revisited by later Muslim rulers and intellectuals for political or religious reasons.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Ottoman sultans, who were thenceforth the most powerful Muslim rulers in western Asia and the Mediterranean, did not use the title of "caliph" at all before the mid-16th century and only did so vaguely and inconsistently afterwards.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The claim that al-Mutawakkil III "transferred" the office of the caliph to the Ottoman sultan during their meeting in Aleppo is a legend that was elaborated in the 19th century and is not corroborated by contemporary accounts.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasid historical period lasting to the Mongol conquest of Baghdad in 1258 CE is considered the Islamic Golden Age.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Islamic Golden Age was inaugurated by the middle of the 8th century by the ascension of the Abbasid Caliphate and the transfer of the capital from Damascus to Baghdad.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasids were influenced by the Qur'anic injunctions and hadith, such as "the ink of a scholar is more holy than the blood of a martyr", stressing the value of knowledge.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Many classic works of antiquity that would otherwise have been lost were translated into Arabic and Persian and later in turn translated into Turkish, Hebrew and Latin.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] During this period the Muslim world was a cauldron of cultures which collected, synthesized and significantly advanced the knowledge gained from the Roman, Chinese, Indian, Persian, Egyptian, North African, Ancient Greek and Medieval Greek civilizations.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Abbasid literary culture in Iraq reflects long-term Mesopotamian narrative continuities, particularly traditions centered on heroic figures and on barriers separating chaos and order.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Core motifs associated with the Epic of Gilgamesh, mediated through the Alexander Romance, including journeys to the world's limits and the containment of chaos, persisted across religious and political change and continued to circulate in late antique Iraq.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Babylonian Talmud, composed by Iraq-based rabbis, preserves parallel traditions concerning Gog and Magog and the imagined edges of the world that confine agents of chaos.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Together, these traditions situate elements of Abbasid literature within a Mesopotamian narrative continuum.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The best-known fiction from the Islamic world is *One Thousand and One Nights*, a collection of fantastical folk tales, legends and parables compiled primarily during the Abbasid era.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The collection is recorded as having originated from an Arabic translation of a Sassanian-era Persian prototype, with likely origins in Indian literary traditions.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Stories from Arabic, Persian, Mesopotamian, and Egyptian folklore and literature were later incorporated.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The epic is believed to have taken shape in the 10th century and reached its final form by the 14th century; the number and type of tales have varied from one manuscript to another.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] All Arabian fantasy tales were often called "Arabian Nights" when translated into English, regardless of whether they appeared in *The Book of One Thousand and One Nights*.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This epic has been influential in the West since it was translated in the 18th century, first by Antoine Galland.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Many imitations were written, especially in France.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Various characters from this epic have themselves become cultural icons in Western culture, such as Aladdin, Sinbad and Ali Baba.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] A famous example of Islamic poetry on romance was *Layla and Majnun*, an originally Arabic story which was further developed by Iranian, Azerbaijani and other poets in the Persian, Azerbaijani, and Turkish languages.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] It is a tragic story of undying love much like the later *Romeo and Juliet*.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Arabic poetry reached its greatest height in the Abbasid era, especially before the loss of central authority and the rise of the Persianate dynasties.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Writers like Abu Tammam and Abu Nuwas were closely connected to the caliphal court in Baghdad during the early 9th century, while others such as al-Mutanabbi received their patronage from regional courts.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Under Harun al-Rashid, Baghdad was renowned for its bookstores, which proliferated after the making of paper was introduced.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Chinese papermakers had been among those taken prisoner by the Arabs at the Battle of Talas in 751.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] As prisoners of war, they were dispatched to Samarkand, where they helped set up the first Arab paper mill.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In time, paper replaced parchment as the medium for writing, and the production of books greatly increased.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] These events had an academic and societal impact that could be broadly compared to the introduction of the printing press in the West.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Paper aided in communication and record-keeping, it also brought a new sophistication and complexity to businesses, banking, and the civil service.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In 794, Jafa al-Barmak built the first paper mill in Baghdad, and from there the technology circulated.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Harun required that paper be employed in government dealings, since something recorded on paper could not easily be changed or removed, and eventually, an entire street in Baghdad's business district was dedicated to selling paper and books.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] One of the common definitions for "Islamic philosophy" is "the style of philosophy produced within the framework of Islamic culture".
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Islamic philosophy, in this definition is neither necessarily concerned with religious issues, nor is exclusively produced by Muslims.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Their works on Aristotle were a key step in the transmission of learning from ancient Greeks to the Islamic world and the West.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] They often corrected the philosopher, encouraging a lively debate in the spirit of ijtihad.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] They also wrote influential original philosophical works, and their thinking was incorporated into Christian philosophy during the Middle Ages, notably by Thomas Aquinas.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Three speculative thinkers, al-Kindi, al-Farabi, and Avicenna, combined Aristotelianism and Neoplatonism with other ideas introduced through Islam, and Avicennism was later established as a result.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Other influential Abbasid philosophers include al-Jahiz, and Ibn al-Haytham (Alhacen).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] As power shifted from the Umayyads to the Abbasids, the architectural styles changed also, from Greco-Roman tradition (which features elements of Hellenistic and Roman representative style) to Eastern tradition which retained their independent architectural traditions from Mesopotamia and Persia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] A defining characteristic of Abbasid architecture in Iraq was the extensive use of stucco and plaster decoration, particularly in interior spaces.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The limited availability of high-quality building stone in Abbasid Iraq contributed to the widespread use of stucco and other malleable materials, which were well suited to repetitive and abstract ornamental decoration.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] At Samarra, these conditions enabled the emergence of a standardized decorative vocabulary that departed from Late Antique naturalism and proved influential well beyond Iraq.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Color also played an important role, particularly the use of blue pigments to enhance stucco and painted surfaces, intensifying abstraction and, in some contexts, carrying protective or apotropaic associations.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Abbasid architecture was particularly influenced by Sasanian architecture, which in turn featured elements present since ancient Mesopotamia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The Christian styles evolved into a style based more on the Sasanian Empire, utilizing mud bricks and baked bricks with carved stucco.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Other architectural innovations and styles were few, such as the four-centered arch, and a dome erected on squinches.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Unfortunately, much was lost due to the ephemeral nature of the stucco and luster tiles.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Another major development was the creation or vast enlargement of cities as they were turned into the capital of the empire, beginning with the creation of Baghdad in 762, which was planned as a walled city with four gates, and a mosque and palace in the center.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Mansur, who was responsible for the creation of Baghdad, also planned the city of Raqqa, along the Euphrates.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Finally, in 836, al-Mu'tasim moved the capital to a new site that he created along the Tigris, called Samarra.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] This city saw 60 years of work, with race-courses and game preserves to add to the atmosphere.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Due to the dry remote nature of the environment, some of the palaces built in this era were isolated havens.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Al-Ukhaidir Fortress is a fine example of this type of building, which has stables, living quarters, and a mosque, all surrounding inner courtyards.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Iraq only has one surviving mausoleum from this era, in Samarra: an octagonal domed structure known as the *Qubbat al-Sulaibiyya*, which is the first known monumental tomb in Islamic architecture and may be the final resting place of al-Muntasir.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Baghdad, the epicenter of the empire, was originally organized in a circular fashion next to the Tigris River, with massive brick walls being constructed in successive rings around the core by a workforce of 100,000 with four huge gates (named Kufa, Basra, Khurasan and Syria).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The central enclosure of the city contained Mansur's palace of 360,000 square feet (33,000 m2) in area and the great mosque of Baghdad, encompassing 90,000 square feet (8,400 m2).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Travel across the Tigris and the network of waterways allowing the drainage of the Euphrates into the Tigris was facilitated by bridges and canals servicing the population.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Outside the Abbasid heartlands, architecture was still influenced by the capital.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In present-day Tunisia, the Great Mosque of Kairouan was founded under the Umayyad dynasty but completely rebuilt in the 9th century under the patronage of the Aghlabids, vassals of the Abbasids.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The styles utilized were mainly Abbasid.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] In Egypt, Ahmad Ibn Tulun commissioned the Ibn Tulun Mosque, completed in 879, that is based on the style of Samarra and is now one of the best-preserved Abbasid-style mosques from this period.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The establishment of Abbasid power based in Iraq, rather than Syria, resulted in a cultural and artistic development influenced not only by the Mediterranean and Middle Eastern traditions but also by connections further afield with India, Central Asia, and China.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] The importation of Chinese ceramics elicited local imitations but also stirred innovations in local production.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Abbasid ceramics became a more important art form with greater emphasis on decoration.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] A major innovation was the emergence of monochrome and polychrome lustreware, a technical achievement that had an important impact on the wider development of Islamic ceramics.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Glassware also became a more important art form and was likely the origin of the lustre technique that was introduced into ceramics.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Few textiles have survived but the production of *tiraz*, textiles with royal inscriptions, is well attested.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Another major art form was calligraphy and manuscript production.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] During the Abbasid period, Arabic calligraphy evolved into a more refined discipline.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Rounded Kufic script was typical and became increasingly stylized.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Parchment only allowed for a few lines of script, but from the late 8th century onward paper began to be produced.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p01] Qur'ans are the main type of book to have survived from this period.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] A number of medieval thinkers and scientists living under Islamic rule played a role in transmitting Islamic science to the Christian West.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In addition, the period saw the recovery of much of the Alexandrian mathematical, geometric and astronomical knowledge, such as that of Euclid and Claudius Ptolemy.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] These recovered mathematical methods were later enhanced and developed by other Islamic scholars, notably by Persian scientists Al-Biruni and Abu Nasr Mansur.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Christians (particularly Nestorian Christians) contributed to the Arab Islamic Civilization during the Umayyads and the Abbasids by translating works of Greek philosophers to Syriac and afterwards to Arabic.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Nestorians played a prominent role in the formation of Arab culture, with the Academy of Gondishapur being prominent in the late Sassanid, Umayyad and early Abbasid periods.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Notably, eight generations of the Nestorian Bukhtishu family served as private doctors to caliphs and sultans between the eighth and eleventh centuries.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Algebra was significantly developed by Persian scientist Muhammad ibn Mūsā al-Khwārizmī during this time in his landmark text, *Kitab al-Jabr wa-l-Muqabala*, from which the term *algebra* is derived.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] He is thus considered to be the father of algebra by some, although the Greek mathematician Diophantus has also been given this title.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The terms *algorism* and *algorithm* are derived from the name of al-Khwarizmi, who was also responsible for introducing the Arabic numerals and Hindu–Arabic numeral system beyond the Indian subcontinent.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Arab scientist Ibn al-Haytham (Alhazen) developed an early scientific method in his *Book of Optics* (1021).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The most important development of the scientific method was the use of experiments to distinguish between competing scientific theories set within a generally empirical orientation, which began among Muslim scientists.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Ibn al-Haytham's empirical proof of the intromission theory of light (that is, that light rays entered the eyes rather than being emitted by them) was particularly important.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Ibn al-Haytham was significant in the history of scientific method, particularly in his approach to experimentation, and has been referred to as the "world's first true scientist".
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Medicine in medieval Islam was an area of science that advanced particularly during the Abbasids' reign.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] During the 9th century, Baghdad contained over 800 doctors, and great discoveries in the understanding of anatomy and diseases were made.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The clinical distinction between measles and smallpox was described during this time.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Famous Persian scientist Ibn Sina (known to the West as Avicenna) produced treatises and works that summarized the vast amount of knowledge that scientists had accumulated, and was very influential through his encyclopedias, *The Canon of Medicine* and *The Book of Healing*.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The work of him and many others directly influenced the research of European scientists during the Renaissance.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Astronomy in medieval Islam was advanced by Al-Battani, who improved the precision of the measurement of the precession of the Earth's axis.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The corrections made to the geocentric model by al-Battani, Averroes, Nasir al-Din al-Tusi, Mo'ayyeduddin Urdi and Ibn al-Shatir were later incorporated into the Copernican heliocentric model.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The astrolabe, though originally developed by the Greeks, was developed further by Islamic astronomers and engineers, and subsequently brought to medieval Europe.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Muslim alchemists influenced medieval European alchemists, particularly the writings attributed to Jābir ibn Hayyān (Geber).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In technology, the Abbasids adopted papermaking from China.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The use of paper spread from China into the caliphate in the 8th century CE, arriving in al-Andalus (Islamic Spain) and then the rest of Europe in the 10th century.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] It was easier to manufacture than parchment, less likely to crack than papyrus, and could absorb ink, making it ideal for making records and copies of the Qur'an.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] "Islamic paper makers devised assembly-line methods of hand-copying manuscripts to turn out editions far larger than any available in Europe for centuries." It was from the Abbasids that the rest of the world learned to make paper from linen.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The knowledge of gunpowder was also transmitted from China via the caliphate, where the formulas for pure potassium nitrate and an explosive gunpowder effect were first developed.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Advances were made in irrigation and farming, using new technology such as the windmill.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Crops such as almonds and citrus fruit were brought to Europe through al-Andalus, and sugar cultivation was gradually adopted by the Europeans.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Apart from the Nile, Tigris and Euphrates, navigable rivers were uncommon, so transport by sea was very important.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Navigational sciences were highly developed, making use of a rudimentary sextant (known as a *kamal*).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] When combined with detailed maps of the period, sailors were able to sail across oceans rather than skirt along the coast.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Abbasid sailors were also responsible for reintroducing large three masted merchant vessels to the Mediterranean.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The name *caravel* may derive from an earlier Arab ship known as the *qārib*.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Arab merchants dominated trade in the Indian Ocean until the arrival of the Portuguese in the 16th century.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Hormuz was an important center for this trade.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] There was also a dense network of trade routes in the Mediterranean, along which Muslim countries traded with each other and with European powers such as Venice or Genoa.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The Silk Road crossing Central Asia passed through the Abbasid caliphate between China and Europe.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Engineers in the Abbasid caliphate made a number of innovative industrial uses of hydropower, and early industrial uses of tidal power, wind power, and petroleum (notably by distillation into kerosene).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The industrial uses of watermills in the Islamic world date back to the 7th century, while horizontal-wheeled and vertical-wheeled water mills were both in widespread use since at least the 9th century.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] By the time of the Crusades, every province throughout the Islamic world had mills in operation, from al-Andalus and North Africa to the Middle East and Central Asia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] These mills performed a variety of agricultural and industrial tasks.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Abbasid engineers also developed machines (such as pumps) incorporating crankshafts, employed gears in mills and water-raising machines, and used dams to provide additional power to watermills and water-raising machines.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Such advances made it possible for many industrial tasks that were previously driven by manual labour in ancient times to be mechanized and driven by machinery instead in the medieval Islamic world.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] It has been argued that the industrial use of waterpower had spread from Islamic to Christian Spain, where fulling mills, paper mills, and forge mills were recorded for the first time in Catalonia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] A number of industries were generated during the Arab Agricultural Revolution, including early industries for textiles, sugar, rope-making, matting, silk, and paper.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Latin translations of the 12th century passed on knowledge of chemistry and instrument making in particular.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The agricultural and handicraft industries also experienced high levels of growth during this period.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] While the Abbasids originally gained power by exploiting the social inequalities against non-Arabs in the Umayyad Empire, during Abbasid rule the empire rapidly Arabized, particularly in the Fertile Crescent region (namely Mesopotamia and the Levant) as had begun under Umayyad rule.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] As knowledge was shared in the Arabic language throughout the empire, many people from different nationalities and religions began to speak Arabic in their everyday lives.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Resources from other languages began to be translated into Arabic, and a unique Islamic identity began to form that fused previous cultures with Arab culture, creating a level of civilization and knowledge that was considered a marvel in Europe at the time.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In contrast to the earlier era, women in Abbasid society were absent from all arenas of the community's central affairs.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] While their Muslim forebears led men into battle, started rebellions, and played an active role in community life, as demonstrated in the Hadith literature, Abbasid women were ideally kept in seclusion.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Conquests had brought enormous wealth and large numbers of slaves to the Muslim elite.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The majority of the slaves were women and children, many of whom had been dependents or harem-members of the defeated Sassanian upper classes.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In the wake of the conquests an elite man could potentially own a thousand slaves, and ordinary soldiers could have ten people serving them.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Even so, slave courtesans (qiyans and jawaris) and princesses produced prestigious and important poetry.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Enough survives to give us access to women's historical experiences, and reveals some vivacious and powerful figures, such as the Sufi mystic Raabi'a al-Adwiyya (714–801 CE), the princess and poet 'Ulayya bint al-Mahdi (777–825 CE), and the singing-girls Shāriyah (c.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Each wife in the Abbasid harem had an additional home or flat, with her own enslaved staff of eunuchs and maidservants.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] When a concubine gave birth to a son, she was elevated in rank to umm walad and also received apartments and (slave) servants as a gift.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The status and treatment of Jews, Christians, and non-Muslims in the Abbasid Caliphate was a complex and continually changing issue.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Dhimmis faced some level of discrimination in Abbasid society: they did not have all the privileges of Muslims and had to pay jizya, a tax on non-Muslims.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] However, as people of the book (non-Muslim monotheists), Jews and Christians were allowed to practice their religion and were not required to convert.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Ecclesiastical authorities discouraged practices such as polygamy and sought to regulate interreligious unions, yet ordinary Christians in Iraq and neighboring regions nonetheless participated in both Christian and Islamic marital practices and households across confessional lines.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Christian men might take multiple wives or marry non-Christians, and interreligious marriages, especially those involving Muslim husbands and Christian women, were a persistent concern for Christian jurists, who viewed them as threatening communal boundaries.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] One of the common aspects of the treatment of the dhimmis is that their treatment depended on who the caliph was at the time.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Some Abbasid rulers, like Al-Mutawakkil (822–861 CE) imposed strict restrictions on what dhimmis could wear in public, often yellow garments that distinguished them from Muslims.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Other restrictions al-Mutawakkil imposed included limiting the role of the dhimmis in government, seizing dhimmi housing and making it harder for dhimmis to become educated.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Most other Abbasid caliphs were not as strict as al-Mutawakkil.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] During the reign of Al-Mansur (754–775 CE), it was common for Jews and Christians to influence the overall culture in the caliphate, specifically in Baghdad.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Jews and Christians did this by participating in scholarly work.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] It was common that laws that were imposed against dhimmis during one caliph's rule were either discarded or not practiced during future caliphs' reigns.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Al-Mansur and al-Mutawakkil both instituted laws that forbade non-Muslims from participating in public office.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Al-Mansur did not follow his own law very closely, bringing dhimmis back to the caliphate's treasury due to the needed expertise of dhimmis in the area of finance.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Al-Mutawakkil followed the law banning dhimmis from public office more seriously, although, soon after his reign, many of the laws concerning dhimmis participating in government were completely unobserved or at least less strictly observed.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] 908–932 CE), who held a similar stance as al-Mutawakkil on barring non-Muslims from public office, himself had multiple Christian secretaries, indicating that non-Muslims still had access to many of the most important figures within the caliphate.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Past having a casual association or just being a secretary to high-ranking Islamic officials, some of them achieved the second highest office after the caliph: the vizier.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Jews and Christians may have had a lower overall status compared to Muslims in the Abbasid Caliphate, but dhimmis were often allowed to hold respectable and even prestigious occupations in some cases, such as doctors and public officeholders.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Jews and Christians were also allowed to be rich even if they were taxed for being a dhimmi.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Dhimmis were capable of moving up and down the social ladder, though this largely depended on the particular caliph.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] An indication as to the social standing of Jews and Christians at the time was their ability to live next to Muslim people.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] While al-Mansur was ruling the caliphate, for instance, it was not uncommon for dhimmis to live in the same neighborhoods as Muslims.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] One of the biggest reasons why dhimmis were allowed to hold prestigious jobs and positions in government is that they were generally important to the well-being of the state and were proficient to excellent with the work at hand.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In general, Muslims, Jews, and Christians had close relations that could be considered positive at times, especially for Jews, in contrast to how Jews were being treated in Europe.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Many of the laws and restrictions that were imposed on dhimmis often resembled other laws that previous states had used to discriminate against a minority religion, specifically Jewish people.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Romans in the fourth century banned Jewish people from holding public offices, banned Roman citizens from converting to Judaism, and often demoted Jews who were serving in the Roman military.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In direct contrast, there was an event in which two viziers, Ibn al-Furat and Ali ibn Isa ibn al-Jarrah, argued about Ibn al-Furat's decision to make a Christian the head of the military.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] A previous vizier, Abu Muhammad al-Hasan al-Bazuri, had done so.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] These laws predated al-Mansur's laws against dhimmis and often had similar restrictions, although Roman emperors were often much more strict on enforcing these laws than many Abbasid caliphs.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Most of Baghdad's Jews were incorporated into the Arab community and considered Arabic their native language.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Some Jews studied Hebrew in their schools and Jewish religious education flourished.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The united Muslim empire allowed Jews to reconstruct links between their dispersed communities throughout the Middle East.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The city's Talmudic institute helped spread the rabbinical tradition to Europe, and the Jewish community in Baghdad went on to establish ten rabbinical schools and twenty-three synagogues.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Baghdad not only contained the tombs of Muslim saints and martyrs, but also the tomb of Yusha, whose corpse had been brought to Iraq during the first migration of the Jews out of the Levant.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] There were large feasts on certain days, as the Muslims of the empire celebrated Christian holidays as well as their own.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] There were two main Islamic feasts: one marked by the end of Ramadan; the other, "the Feast of Sacrifice".
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The former was especially joyful because children would purchase decorations and sweetmeats; people prepared the best food and bought new clothes.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] At midmorning, the caliph, wearing Muhammad's thobe, would guide officials, accompanied by armed soldiers to the Great Mosque, where he led prayers.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] After the prayer, all those in attendance would exchange the best wishes and hug their kin and companions.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] During those limited number of nights, the palaces were lit up and boats on the Tigris hung lights.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] It was said that Baghdad "glittered 'like a bride'".
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] During the Feast of Sacrifice, sheep were butchered in public arenas and the caliph participated in a large-scale sacrifice in the palace courtyard.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Afterward, the meat would be divided and given to the poor.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In addition to these two holidays, Shias celebrated the birthdays of Fatimah and Ali ibn Abi Talib.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Matrimonies and births in the royal family were observed by all in the empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The announcement that one of the caliph's sons could recite the Koran smoothly was greeted by communal jubilation.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] When Harun developed this holy talent, the people lit torches and decorated the streets with wreaths of flowers, and his father, Al-Mahdi, freed 500 slaves.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Of all the holidays imported from other cultures and religions, the one most celebrated in Baghdad (a city with many Persians) was Nowruz, which celebrated the arrival of spring.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In a ceremonial ablution introduced by Persian troops, residents sprinkled themselves with water and ate almond cakes.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The palaces of the imperial family were lit up for six days and nights.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The Abbasids also celebrated the Persian holiday of Mihraj, which marked the onset of winter (signified with pounding drums), and Sadar, when homes burned incense and the masses would congregate along the Tigris to witness princes and viziers pass by.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The Abbasid army amassed an array of siege equipment, such as catapults, mangonels, battering rams, ladders, grappling irons, and hooks.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] All such weaponry was operated by military engineers.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] However, the primary siege weapon was the *manjaniq*, a type of siege weapon that was comparable to the trebuchet employed in Western medieval times.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] From the seventh century onward, it had largely replaced torsion artillery.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] By Harun al-Rashid's time, the Abbasid army employed fire grenades.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The Abbasids also utilized field hospitals and ambulances drawn by camels.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The cavalry was entirely covered in iron, with helmets.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Similar to medieval knights, their only exposed spots were the end of their noses and small openings in front of their eyes.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Their foot soldiers were issued spears, swords, and pikes, and (in line with Persian fashion) trained to stand so solidly that, one contemporary wrote "you would have thought them held fast by clamps of bronze".
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Although the Abbasids never retained a substantial regular army, the caliph could recruit a considerable number of soldiers in a short time when needed from levies.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] There were also cohorts of regular troops who received steady pay and a special forces unit.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] At any moment, 125,000 Muslim soldiers could be assembled along the Byzantine frontier, Baghdad, Medina, Damascus, Rayy, and other geostrategic locations in order to quell any unrest.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] During the Abbasid revolution, Abu Muslim's Khorasani army, composed largely of Arab settlers disillusioned with Umayyad rule, marched under black banners, forming a powerful force that swept westward in open revolt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In Baghdad there were many Abbasid military leaders who were or said they were of Arab descent.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] However, it is clear that most of the ranks were of Iranian origin, the vast majority being from Khurasan and Transoxiana, not from western Iran or Azerbaijan.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Most of the Khurasani soldiers who brought the Abbasids to power were Arabs.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The standing army of the Muslims in Khurasan was overwhelmingly Arab.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The unit organization of the Abbasids was designed with the goal of ethnic and racial equality among supporters.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] When Abu Muslim recruited officers along the Silk Road, he registered them based not on their tribal or ethno-national affiliations but on their current places of residence.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Under the Abbasids, Iranian peoples became better represented in the army and bureaucracy as compared to before.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] He abolished the old *jund* system created by Umar and diverted the salaries of the original Arab military descendants to the Turkic slave soldiers.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The Turkic soldiers transformed the style of warfare, as they were known as capable horse archers, trained from childhood to ride.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] This military was now drafted from the ethnic groups of the faraway borderlands, and were completely separate from the rest of society.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] This led to the decline of the caliphate starting with the Anarchy at Samarra.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] As a result of such a vast Empire, the caliphate was decentralized and divided into 24 provinces.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Harun's vizier enjoyed close to unchecked powers.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Under Harun, a special "bureau of confiscation" was created.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] This governmental wing made it possible for the vizier to seize the property and riches of any corrupt governor or civil servant.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In addition, it allowed governors to confiscate the estates of lower-ranking officials.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Finally, the caliph could impose the same penalty on a vizier who fell from grace.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] As one later caliph put it: "The vizier is our representative throughout the land and amongst our subjects.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Every regional metropolis had a post office and hundreds of roads were paved in order to link the imperial capital with other cities and towns.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The empire employed a system of relays to deliver mail.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The central post office in Baghdad even had a map with directions that noted the distances between each town.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The roads were provided with roadside inns, hospices, and wells and could reach eastward through Persia and Central Asia, to as far as China.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The post office not only enhanced civil services but also served as intelligence for the caliph.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Mailmen were employed as spies who kept an eye on local affairs.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Early in the days of the caliphate, the Barmakids took the responsibility of shaping the civil service.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The family had roots in a Buddhist monastery in northern Afghanistan.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In the early 8th century, the family converted to Islam and began to take on a sizable part of the civil administration for the Abbasids.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Capital poured into the caliphate's treasury from a variety of taxes, including a real estate tax; a levy on cattle, gold and silver, and commercial wares; a special tax on non-Muslims; and customs dues.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Under Harun al-Rashid, maritime trade through the Persian Gulf thrived, with Arab vessels trading as far south as Madagascar and as far east as China, Korea, and Japan.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The growing economy of Baghdad and other cities inevitably led to the demand for luxury items and formed a class of entrepreneurs who organized long-range caravans for the trade and then the distribution of their goods.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] A whole section in the East Baghdad suq was dedicated to Chinese goods.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Much of this direct maritime trade was oriented toward Iraqi markets, particularly Basra and Baghdad, which functioned as major destinations for goods arriving from Tang China.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] From the seventh to the tenth centuries, merchants from the Gulf served Iraqi markets through direct sea routes linking the Persian Gulf to the South China coast, especially Guangzhou, as attested by both contemporary textual sources and archaeological evidence.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The ninth-century Belitung shipwreck, carrying a large cargo of Chinese ceramics, illustrates the scale of this trade and its connection to demand in Iraq and the wider Abbasid realm.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Arabs traded with the Baltic region and made it as far north as the British Isles.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Tens of thousands of Arab coins have been discovered in parts of Russia and Sweden, which bear witness to the comprehensive trade networks set up by the Abbasids.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] King Offa of Mercia (in England) minted gold coins similar to those of the Abbasids in the eighth century.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Muslim merchants employed ports in Bandar Siraf, Basra, and Aden and some Red Sea ports to travel and trade with India and South East Asia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Land routes were also utilized through Central Asia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Arab businessmen were present in China as early as the eighth century.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Arab merchants sailed the Caspian Sea to reach and trade with Bukhara and Samarkand.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] During the ninth and tenth centuries, large quantities of opaque glazed pottery were produced in southern Iraq, within the heartlands of the Abbasid Caliphate, and exported as a mass-produced commercial commodity.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Finds of this Iraqi ware at sites across the Middle East, South Africa, and Southeast Asia demonstrate sustained commercial interaction between Iraq and the wider Indian Ocean world.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Most of the exported vessels were standardized and practical in design, indicating that they were produced for large-scale commercial trade rather than for elite or luxury use.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Many caravans and goods never made it to their intended destinations.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Some Chinese exports perished in fires, while other ships sank.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] It was said that anybody who made it to China and back unharmed was blessed by God.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Common sea routes were also plagued by pirates who built and crewed vessels that were faster than most merchant ships.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] It is said that many of the adventures at sea in the Sinbad tales were based on historical fiction of mariners of the day.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The Abbasids also established overland trade with Africa, largely for gold and slaves.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] When trade with Europe ceased due to hostilities, Jews served as a link between the two hostile worlds.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] The Abbasids engaged in extensive trade with the Italian maritime republics of Venice and Genoa, from the 11th century.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Venetian merchants facilitated the exchange of high-value goods such as spices, silk, and precious metals from the East.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] In return, Venice exported European manufactured goods and luxury items.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] While Genoese merchants traded in luxury goods like spices, textiles, and other high-demand items.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] Genoa's strategic position in the Mediterranean enabled it to integrate into the broader Mediterranean trade network, connecting the Abbasid Caliphate with other European markets.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] These trade relations played a key role in linking the medieval Mediterranean with the broader Islamic world.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abbasid-caliphate-p02] This exchange of goods, alongside cultural and technological transfers, fostered a more interconnected medieval global economy.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abtu] Abtu was also the ancient word for the western or west of something.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abtu] This was then understood as the place where the days passage of the sun across the sky finishes so for ancient Egypt where the sun dies each day and passes into the dark underworld.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abtu] Furthermore, the goddess Isis is said to have transformed into the Abtu, perhaps therefore lending to the creature its sacred state.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abtu] Isis, as 'Abtu, Great Fish of the Abyss,' was identified with the penis-swallower of the Osiris in the legend of Osiris within the city of Oxyrhynchus, and named the city after the sacred fish (Oxyrhynchus means "sharp nosed fish").
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abtu] The fish cult spread to many parts of Egypt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/abtu] The mythological Abtu also was known to accompany the barque of Ra across the sky at sunrise.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/academic-imperialism] Academic imperialism has been defined either in the context of certain disciplines or subdisciplines as oppressing others or (more often) as part of political imperialism that has resulted in inequality between academia in the First World (the West) and Third World.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/academic-imperialism] In the intradisciplinary context, an example of imperialistic behavior was the dismissive attitude of the 1920s-1930s adherents of behavioral psychology in the United States towards non-behavioral psychologists.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/academic-imperialism] In the international context, academic imperialism began in the colonial period when the colonial powers designed and implemented a system of academia in their colonial territories.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/academic-imperialism] Raju claims academic imperialism emerged thanks to racism among native colonial elites.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/academic-imperialism] Syed Farid Alatas calls this "academic neo-colonialism".
[src:kingdom-of-kush/academic-imperialism] International academic imperialism generates academic dependency, or the dependency of non-Western scholars on Western academia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/academic-imperialism] In non-Western countries, science is still dependent on institutions and ideas of Western science, which are often transplanted from Western countries.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/academic-imperialism] Another example is the dominance of English language in the world of international academia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The **Achaemenid Empire** (/ə.ˈkiː.mə.nɪd/, *ə-KEE-mə-nid*; Old Persian: 𐎧𐏁𐏂, *Xšāça*, lit.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] 'The Empire' or 'The Kingdom') was an ancient Iranian empire founded by Cyrus the Great of the Achaemenid dynasty in 550 BC.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] At peak, its territorial extent was roughly 5.5 million square kilometres (2.1 million square miles), making it the largest empire of its time.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Based in the Iranian plateau, it stretched from the Balkans and Cyrenaica in the west to the Indus Valley in the east, including Anatolia, Cyprus, Mesopotamia, the Levant, the South Caucasus, parts of Eastern Arabia, and large parts of Central Asia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] By the 7th century BC, the region of Persis, located in the southwestern part of the Iranian plateau, had been settled by Persian people.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] From Persis, Cyrus rose and defeated Media, Lydia, and the Neo-Babylonian Empire, thus marking the establishment of a new imperial polity in the ancient Near East.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] While its conquests were largely successful in most regions, the Achaemenid Empire's attempts to expand into Greece proved extremely difficult over the course of decades of wars and multiple kings, ultimately resulting in its defeat in the Greek mainland.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 330 BC, amidst a Greek military campaign that began in 336 BC, the Achaemenid Empire was conquered in its entirety by Alexander the Great, who annexed it to his Macedonian Empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Upon Alexander's death, which sparked the beginning of the Hellenistic period in 323 BC, the majority of the former Achaemenid Empire's territories came under the rule of the Seleucid Empire and the Ptolemaic Kingdom.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Almost a century later, Iranian elites in the central plateau successfully reclaimed power from the Seleucids and established the Parthian Empire, which existed for nearly half a millennium before being succeeded by the Iranian Sasanian Empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Many of these systems were adopted and expanded upon by later empires in the Greco-Roman world and beyond.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire is named after Achaemenes, who is credited as the progenitor of the Achaemenid dynasty.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The term *Achaemenid* means "of the family of the Achaemenis/Achaemenes" (Old Persian: 𐏃𐎧𐎠𐎶𐎴𐎡𐏁, romanized: *Haxāmaniš*; a bahuvrihi compound translating to "having a friend's mind").
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Achaemenes was himself a minor seventh-century ruler of the Anshan in southwestern Iran, and a vassal of Assyria.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Around 850 BC the original nomadic people who began the empire called themselves the *Parsa* and their constantly shifting territory *Parsua*, for the most part localized around Persis.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The name "Persia" is a Greek and Latin pronunciation of the native word referring to the country of the people originating from Persis (Old Persian: 𐎱𐎠𐎼𐎿, romanized: *Pārsa*).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian term 𐎧𐏁𐏂 *Xšāça*, literally meaning "The Kingdom", was used to refer to the Empire formed by their multinational state.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire was created by nomadic Persians.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians were Iranian people who arrived in what is today Iran c.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] 1000 BC and settled a region including north-western Iran, the Zagros Mountains and Persis alongside the native Elamites.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians were originally nomadic pastoralists in the western Iranian Plateau.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire may not have been the first Iranian empire, as the Medes, another group of Iranian people, possibly established a short-lived empire when they played a major role in overthrowing the Assyrians.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenids were initially rulers of the Elamite city of Anshan near the modern city of Marvdasht; the title "King of Anshan" was an adaptation of the earlier Elamite title "King of Susa and Anshan".
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] There are conflicting accounts of the identities of the earliest Kings of Anshan.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Cyrus Cylinder (the oldest extant genealogy of the Achaemenids) the kings of Anshan were Teispes, Cyrus I, Cambyses I and Cyrus II, also known as Cyrus the Great, who founded the empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The later Behistun Inscription, written by Darius the Great, claims that Teispes was the son of Achaemenes and that Darius is also descended from Teispes through a different line, but no earlier texts mention Achaemenes.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] In Herodotus' Histories, he writes that Cyrus the Great was the son of Cambyses I and Mandane of Media, the daughter of Astyages, the king of the Median Empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus revolted against the Median Empire in 553 BC, and in 550 BC succeeded in defeating the Medes, capturing Astyages and taking the Median capital city of Ecbatana.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Once in control of Ecbatana, Cyrus styled himself as the successor to Astyages and assumed control of the entire empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] By inheriting Astyages' empire, he also inherited the territorial conflicts the Medes had with both Lydia and the Neo-Babylonian Empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] King Croesus of Lydia sought to take advantage of the new international situation by advancing into what had previously been Median territory in Asia Minor.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus led a counterattack which not only fought off Croesus' armies, but also led to the capture of Sardis and the fall of the Lydian Kingdom in 546 BC.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus placed Pactyes in charge of collecting tribute in Lydia and left, but once Cyrus had left Pactyes instigated a rebellion against Cyrus.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus sent the Median general Mazares to deal with the rebellion, and Pactyes was captured.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mazares, and after his death Harpagus, set about reducing all the cities which had taken part in the rebellion.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The subjugation of Lydia took about four years in total.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] When the power in Ecbatana changed hands from the Medes to the Persians, many tributaries to the Median Empire believed their situation had changed and revolted against Cyrus.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] This forced Cyrus to fight wars against Bactria and the nomadic Saka in Central Asia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] During these wars, Cyrus established several garrison towns in Central Asia, including the Cyropolis.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nothing is known of Persia–Babylon relations between 547 and 539 BC, but it is likely that there were hostilities between the two empires for several years leading up to the war of 540–539 BC and the Fall of Babylon.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] In October 539 BC, Cyrus won a battle against the Babylonians at Opis, then took Sippar without a fight before finally capturing the city of Babylon on 12 October, where the Babylonian king Nabonidus was taken prisoner.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus is credited with freeing the Jews from the Babylonian captivity, permitting their return to Judah, and authorizing the rebuilding of Jerusalem, including the Second Temple.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 530 BC, Cyrus died and was succeeded by his eldest son Cambyses II, while his younger son Bardiya received a large territory in Central Asia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] By 525 BC, Cambyses had successfully subjugated Phoenicia and Cyprus and was making preparations to invade Egypt with the newly created Persian navy.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Pharaoh Amasis II had died in 526, and had been succeeded by Psamtik III, resulting in the defection of key Egyptian allies to the Persians.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Psamtik positioned his army at Pelusium in the Nile Delta.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] He was soundly defeated by the Persians in the Battle of Pelusium before fleeing to Memphis, where the Persians defeated him and took him prisoner.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] After attempting a failed revolt, Psamtik III promptly committed suicide.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus depicts Cambyses as openly antagonistic to the Egyptian people and their gods, cults, temples, and priests, in particular stressing the murder of the sacred bull Apis.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] He says that these actions led to a madness that caused him to kill his brother Bardiya (who Herodotus says was killed in secret), his own sister-wife and Croesus of Lydia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] He then concludes that Cambyses completely lost his mind, and all later classical authors repeat the themes of Cambyses' impiety and madness.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, this is based on spurious information, as the epitaph of Apis from 524 BC shows that Cambyses participated in the funeral rites of Apis styling himself as pharaoh.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following the conquest of Egypt, the Libyans and the Greeks of Cyrene and Barca in present-day eastern Libya (Cyrenaica) surrendered to Cambyses and sent tribute without a fight.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cambyses then planned invasions of Carthage, the oasis of Ammon and Ethiopia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus claims that the naval invasion of Carthage was canceled because the Phoenicians, who made up a large part of Cambyses' fleet, refused to take up arms against their own people, but modern historians doubt whether an invasion of Carthage was ever planned at all.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, Cambyses dedicated his efforts to the other two campaigns, aiming to improve the Empire's strategic position in Africa by conquering the Kingdom of Meroë and taking strategic positions in the western oases.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] To this end, he established a garrison at Elephantine consisting mainly of Jewish soldiers, who remained stationed at Elephantine throughout Cambyses' reign.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Furthermore, in two inscriptions of Darius, Nubia is listed as one of the lands in the empire, and a Nubian delegation is depicted in Persepolis on the Apadana reliefs which visually present the lands of Darius’ empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] These suggest that Cambyses saw success in subduing Nubia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The events surrounding Cambyses's death and Bardiya's succession are greatly debated as there are many conflicting accounts.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to Herodotus, as Bardiya's assassination had been committed in secret, the majority of Persians still believed him to be alive.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] This allowed two Magi to rise up against Cambyses, with one of them sitting on the throne able to impersonate Bardiya because of their remarkable physical resemblance and shared name (Smerdis in Herodotus's accounts).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Ctesias writes that when Cambyses had Bardiya killed he immediately put the magus Sphendadates in his place as satrap of Bactria due to a remarkable physical resemblance.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Two of Cambyses' confidants then conspired to usurp Cambyses and put Sphendadates on the throne under the guise of Bardiya.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Behistun Inscription, written by the following king Darius the Great, a magus named Gaumata impersonated Bardiya and incited a revolution in Persia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Whatever the exact circumstances of the revolt, Cambyses heard news of it in the summer of 522 BC and began to return from Egypt, but he was wounded in the thigh in Syria and died of gangrene, so Bardiya's impersonator became king.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The account of Darius is the earliest, and although the later historians all agree on the key details of the story, that a magus impersonated Bardiya and took the throne, this may have been a story created by Darius to justify his own usurpation.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Iranologist Pierre Briant hypothesises that Bardiya was not killed by Cambyses, but waited until his death in the summer of 522 BC to claim his legitimate right to the throne as he was then the only male descendant of the royal family.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Briant says that although the hypothesis of a deception by Darius is generally accepted today, "nothing has been established with certainty at the present time, given the available evidence".
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Behistun inscription, Gaumata ruled for seven months before being overthrown in 522 BC by Darius the Great (Old Persian *Dāryavuš*, "who holds firm the good", also known as *Darayarahush*).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Magi, though persecuted, continued to exist, and a year following the death of the first pseudo-Smerdis (*Gaumata*), saw a second pseudo-Smerdis (*Vahyazdāta*) attempt a coup.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The coup, though initially successful, failed.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus writes that the native leadership debated the best form of government for the empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Macedonian king Amyntas I surrendered his country to the Persians in about 512–511.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The subjugation of Macedonia was part of Persian military operations initiated by Darius the Great (521–486) in 513—after immense preparations—a huge Achaemenid army invaded the Balkans and tried to defeat the European Scythians roaming to the north of the Danube river.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius' army subjugated several Thracian people, and virtually all other regions that touch the European part of the Black Sea, such as parts of modern Bulgaria, Romania, Ukraine, and Russia, before it returned to Asia Minor.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius left in Europe one of his commanders named Megabazus whose task was to accomplish conquests in the Balkans.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian troops subjugated gold-rich Thrace, the coastal Greek cities, and defeated and conquered the powerful Paeonians.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Finally, Megabazus sent envoys to Amyntas, demanding acceptance of Persian domination, which the Macedonians did.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Balkans provided many soldiers for the multi-ethnic Achaemenid army.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Many of the Macedonian and Persian elite intermarried, such as the Persian official Bubares who married Amyntas' daughter, Gygaea.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Family ties that the Macedonian rulers Amyntas and Alexander enjoyed with Bubares ensured them good relations with the Persian kings Darius and Xerxes I, who was also known as Xerxes the Great.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian invasion led indirectly to Macedonia's rise in power and Persia had some common interests in the Balkans; with Persian aid, the Macedonians stood to gain much at the expense of some Balkan tribes such as the Paeonians and Greeks.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] All in all, the Macedonians were "willing and useful Persian allies.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Macedonian soldiers fought against Athens and Sparta in Xerxes I's army.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians referred to both Greeks and Macedonians as *Yauna* ("Ionians", their term for "Greeks"), and to Macedonians specifically as *Yaunã Takabara* or "Greeks with hats that look like shields", possibly referring to the Macedonian kausia hat.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ionian Revolt in 499 BC, and associated revolts in Aeolis, Doris, Cyprus, and Caria, were military rebellions by several regions of Asia Minor against Persian rule, lasting from 499 to 493 BC.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] At the heart of the rebellion was the dissatisfaction of the Greek cities of Asia Minor with the tyrants appointed by Persia to rule them, along with the individual actions of two Milesian tyrants, Histiaeus and Aristagoras.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 499 BC, the then-tyrant of Miletus, Aristagoras, launched a joint expedition with the Persian satrap Artaphernes to conquer Naxos, in an attempt to bolster his position in Miletus, both financially and in terms of prestige.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The mission was a debacle, and sensing his imminent removal as a tyrant, Aristagoras chose to incite the whole of Ionia into rebellion against the Persian king, Darius I, who was commonly known as Darius the Great.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians continued to reduce the cities along the west coast that still held out against them, before finally imposing a peace settlement in 493 BC on Ionia that was generally considered to be both just and fair.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ionian Revolt constituted the first major conflict between Greece and the Achaemenid Empire, and as such represents the first phase of the Greco-Persian Wars.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Asia Minor had been brought back into the Persian fold, but Darius had vowed to punish Athens and Eretria for their support of the revolt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Moreover, seeing that the political situation in Greece posed a continued threat to the stability of his Empire, he decided to embark on the conquest of all of Greece.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The first campaign of the invasion was to bring the territories in the Balkan peninsula back within the empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian grip over these territories had loosened following the Ionian Revolt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 492 BC, the Persian general Mardonius re-subjugated Thrace and made Macedonia a fully subordinate part of the empire; it had been a vassal as early as the late 6th century BC but retained a great deal of autonomy.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, in 490 BC the Persian forces were defeated by the Athenians at the Battle of Marathon and Darius I would die before having the chance to launch an invasion of Greece.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Xerxes I (485–465 BC, Old Persian *Xšayārša* "Hero Among Kings"), son of Darius I, vowed to complete the job.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] He organized a massive invasion aiming to conquer Greece.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] His army entered Greece from the north in the spring of 480 BC, meeting little or no resistance through Macedonia and Thessaly, but was delayed by a small Greek force for three days at Thermopylae.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] A simultaneous naval battle of Artemisium was tactically indecisive as large storms destroyed ships from both sides.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The battle was stopped prematurely when the Greeks received news of the defeat at Thermopylae and retreated.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The battle was a tactical victory for the Persians, giving them uncontested control of Artemisium and the Aegean Sea.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following his victory at the Battle of Thermopylae, Xerxes sacked the evacuated city of Athens and prepared to meet the Greeks at the strategic Isthmus of Corinth and the Saronic Gulf.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 480 BC the Greeks won a decisive victory over the Persian fleet at the Battle of Salamis and forced Xerxes to retire to Sardis.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The land army which he left in Greece under Mardonius retook Athens but was eventually destroyed in 479 BC at the Battle of Plataea.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The final defeat of the Persians at Mycale encouraged the Greek cities of Asia to revolt, and the Persians lost all of their territories in Europe with Macedonia once again becoming independent.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Xerxes was assassinated in his bed, though ancient accounts conflict significantly.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The assassination is attributed by Greek and Roman sources to Artabanus, though a Babylonian tablet attributes it to Xerxes' son.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Xerxes I was assassinated, he was succeeded by his eldest surviving son Artaxerxes I.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was during his reign that Elamite ceased to be the language of government, and Aramaic gained in importance.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was probably during this reign that the solar calendar was introduced as the national calendar.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under Artaxerxes I, Zoroastrianism became the *de facto* religion of the empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Persia had been defeated at the Battle of Eurymedon (469 or 466 BC), military action between Greece and Persia was halted.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Artaxerxes I took power, he introduced a new Persian strategy of weakening the Athenians by funding their enemies in Greece.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] This indirectly caused the Athenians to move the treasury of the Delian League from the island of Delos to the Athenian acropolis.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] This funding practice inevitably prompted renewed fighting in 450 BC, where the Greeks attacked at the Battle of Cyprus.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Cimon's failure to attain much in this expedition, the Peace of Callias was agreed between Athens, Argos and Persia in 449 BC.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes offered asylum to Themistocles, who was the winner of the Battle of Salamis, after Themistocles was ostracized from Athens.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, Artaxerxes gave him Magnesia, Myus, and Lampsacus to maintain him in bread, meat, and wine.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] In addition, Artaxerxes I gave him Palaescepsis to provide him with clothes, and he also gave him Percote with bedding for his house.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Artaxerxes died in 424 BC at Susa, his body was taken to the tomb already built for him in the Naqsh-e Rustam Necropolis.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was Persian tradition that kings begin constructing their own tombs while they were still alive.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes I was immediately succeeded by his eldest and only legitimate son, Xerxes II.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, after a few days on the throne, he was assassinated while drunk by Pharnacyas and Menostanes on the orders of his illegitimate brother Sogdianus, who apparently had gained the support of his regions.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sogdianus reigned for six months and fifteen days before being captured by his half-brother, Ochus, who had rebelled against him.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sogdianus was executed by being suffocated in ash because Ochus had promised he would not die by the sword, by poison or by hunger.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Ochus then took the royal name Darius II.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius' ability to defend his position on the throne ended the short power vacuum.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] From 412 BC Darius II, at the insistence of Tissaphernes, gave support first to Athens, then to Sparta, but in 407 BC, Darius' son Cyrus the Younger was appointed to replace Tissaphernes and aid was given entirely to Sparta which finally defeated Athens in 404 BC.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the same year, Darius fell ill and died in Babylon.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] His death gave an Egyptian rebel named Amyrtaeus the opportunity to throw off Persian control over Egypt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] At his death bed, Darius' Babylonian wife Parysatis pleaded with him to have her second eldest son Cyrus (the Younger) crowned, but Darius refused.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Queen Parysatis favoured Cyrus more than her eldest son Artaxerxes II.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Plutarch relates (probably on the authority of Ctesias) that the displaced Tissaphernes came to the new king on his coronation day to warn him that his younger brother Cyrus (the Younger) was preparing to assassinate him during the ceremony.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes had Cyrus arrested and would have had him executed if their mother Parysatis had not intervened.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus was then sent back as Satrap of Lydia, where he prepared an armed rebellion.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus assembled a large army, including a contingent of Ten Thousand Greek mercenaries, and made his way deeper into Persia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The army of Cyrus was stopped by the royal Persian army of Artaxerxes II at Cunaxa in 401 BC, where Cyrus was killed.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ten Thousand Greek Mercenaries including Xenophon were now deep in Persian territory and were at risk of attack.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] So they searched for others to offer their services to but eventually had to return to Greece.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II was the longest reigning of the Achaemenid kings and it was during this 45-year period of relative peace and stability that many of the monuments of the era were constructed.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes moved the capital back to Persepolis, which he greatly extended.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, the summer capital at Ecbatana was lavishly extended with gilded columns and roof tiles of silver and copper.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The extraordinary innovation of the Zoroastrian shrines can also be dated to his reign, and it was probably during this period that Zoroastrianism spread from Armenia throughout Asia Minor and the Levant.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The construction of temples, though serving a religious purpose, was not a purely selfless act, as they also served as an important source of income.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] From the Babylonian kings, the Achaemenids adopted the concept of a mandatory temple tax, a one-tenth tithe which all inhabitants paid to the temple nearest to their land or another source of income.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II became involved in a war with Persia's erstwhile allies, the Spartans, who, under Agesilaus II, invaded Asia Minor.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] To redirect the Spartans' attention to Greek affairs, Artaxerxes II subsidized their enemies: in particular the Athenians, Thebans and Corinthians.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] These subsidies helped to engage the Spartans in what would become known as the Corinthian War.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 387 BC, Artaxerxes II betrayed his allies and came to an arrangement with Sparta, and in the Treaty of Antalcidas he forced his erstwhile allies to come to terms.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] This treaty restored control of the Greek cities of Ionia and Aeolis on the Anatolian coast to the Persians while giving Sparta dominance on the Greek mainland.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 385 BC he campaigned against the Cadusians.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Although successful against the Greeks, Artaxerxes II had more trouble with the Egyptians, who had successfully revolted against him at the beginning of his reign.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] An attempt to reconquer Egypt in 373 BC was completely unsuccessful, but in his waning years the Persians did manage to defeat a joint Egyptian–Spartan effort to conquer Phoenicia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] He quashed the Revolt of the Satraps in 372–362 BC.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] He is reported to have had a number of wives.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] His main wife was Stateira, until she was poisoned by Artaxerxes II's mother Parysatis in about 400 BC.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Another chief wife was a Greek woman of Phocaea named Aspasia (not the same as the concubine of Pericles).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II is said to have had more than 115 sons from 350 wives.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 358 BC Artaxerxes II died and was succeeded by his son Artaxerxes III.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 355 BC, Artaxerxes III forced Athens to conclude a peace which required the city's forces to leave Asia Minor and to acknowledge the independence of its rebellious allies.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes started a campaign against the rebellious Cadusians, but he managed to appease both of the Cadusian kings.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] One individual who successfully emerged from this campaign was Darius Codomannus, who later occupied the Persian throne as Darius III.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes III then ordered the disbanding of all the satrapal armies of Asia Minor, as he felt that they could no longer guarantee peace in the west and was concerned that these armies equipped the western satraps with the means to revolt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The order was however ignored by Artabazos II of Phrygia, who asked for the help of Athens in a rebellion against the king.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Orontes of Mysia also supported Artabazos and the combined forces managed to defeat the forces sent by Artaxerxes III in 354 BC.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, in 353 BC, they were defeated by Artaxerxes III's army and were disbanded.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Orontes was pardoned by the king, while Artabazos fled to the safety of the court of Philip II of Macedon.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] 351 BC, Artaxerxes embarked on a campaign to recover Egypt, which had revolted under his father, Artaxerxes II.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] At the same time, a rebellion had broken out in Asia Minor, which, being supported by Thebes, threatened to become serious.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Levying a vast army, Artaxerxes invaded Egypt and engaged in fighting with Nectanebo II.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] After a year of fighting the Egyptian Pharaoh, Nectanebo inflicted a crushing defeat on the Persians with the support of mercenaries led by the Greek generals Diophantus and Lamius.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes was compelled to retreat and postpone his plans to reconquer Egypt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Soon after this defeat, there were rebellions in Phoenicia, Asia Minor and Cyprus.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] , with a label in Greek (ΔΑΡΕΙΟΣ, top right) giving his name.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 343 BC, Artaxerxes committed responsibility for the suppression of the Cyprian rebels to Idrieus, prince of Caria, who employed 8,000 Greek mercenaries and forty triremes, commanded by Phocion the Athenian, and Evagoras, son of the elder Evagoras, the Cypriot monarch.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes initiated a counter-offensive against Sidon by commanding Belesys, satrap of Syria, and Mazaeus, satrap of Cilicia, to invade the city and to keep the Phoenicians in check.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Both satraps suffered crushing defeats at the hands of Tennes, the Sidonese king, who was aided by 40,000 Greek mercenaries sent to him by Nectanebo II and commanded by Mentor of Rhodes.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] As a result, the Persian forces were driven out of Phoenicia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] After this, Artaxerxes personally led an army of 330,000 men against Sidon.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes' army comprised 300,000-foot soldiers, 30,000 cavalry, 300 triremes, and 500 transports or provision ships.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] After gathering this army, he sought assistance from the Greeks.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Though refused aid by Athens and Sparta, he succeeded in obtaining a thousand Theban heavy-armed hoplites under Lacrates, three thousand Argives under Nicostratus, and six thousand Æolians, Ionians, and Dorians from the Greek cities of Asia Minor.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] This Greek support was numerically small, amounting to no more than 10,000 men, but it formed, together with the Greek mercenaries from Egypt who went over to him afterward, the force on which he placed his chief reliance, and to which the ultimate success of his expedition was mainly due.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The approach of Artaxerxes sufficiently weakened the resolution of Tennes that he endeavoured to purchase his own pardon by delivering up 100 principal citizens of Sidon into the hands of the Persian king and then admitting Artaxerxes within the defences of the town.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes had the 100 citizens transfixed with javelins, and when 500 more came out as supplicants to seek his mercy, Artaxerxes consigned them to the same fate.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sidon was then burnt to the ground, either by Artaxerxes or by the Sidonian citizens.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Forty thousand people died in the conflagration.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes sold the ruins at a high price to speculators, who calculated on reimbursing themselves by the treasures which they hoped to dig out from among the ashes.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Tennes was later put to death by Artaxerxes.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes later sent Jews who supported the revolt to Hyrcania on the south coast of the Caspian Sea.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The reduction of Sidon was followed closely by the invasion of Egypt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 343 BC, Artaxerxes III, in addition to his 330,000 Persians, had now a force of 14,000 Greeks furnished by the Greek cities of Asia Minor: 4,000 under Mentor, consisting of the troops that he had brought to the aid of Tennes from Egypt; 3,000 sent by Argos; and 1,000 from Thebes.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] He divided these troops into three bodies, and placed at the head of each a Persian and a Greek.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Greek commanders were Lacrates of Thebes, Mentor of Rhodes and Nicostratus of Argos while the Persians were led by Rhossaces, Aristazanes, and Bagoas, the chief of the eunuchs.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nectanebo II resisted with an army of 100,000 of whom 20,000 were Greek mercenaries.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nectanebo II occupied the Nile and its various branches with his large navy.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The character of the country, intersected by numerous canals and full of strongly fortified towns, was in his favour and Nectanebo II might have been expected to offer a prolonged, if not even a successful resistance.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, he lacked good generals, and, over-confident in his own powers of command, he was out-maneuvered by the Greek mercenary generals, and his forces were eventually defeated by the combined Persian armies.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] After his defeat, Nectanebo hastily fled to Memphis, leaving the fortified towns to be defended by their garrisons.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] These garrisons consisted of partly Greek and partly Egyptian troops; between whom jealousies and suspicions were easily sown by the Persian leaders.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] As a result, the Persians were able to rapidly reduce numerous towns across Lower Egypt and were advancing upon Memphis when Nectanebo decided to quit the country and flee southwards to Ethiopia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian army completely routed the Egyptians and occupied the Lower Delta of the Nile.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following Nectanebo fleeing to Ethiopia, all of Egypt submitted to Artaxerxes.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Jews in Egypt were sent either to Babylon or to the south coast of the Caspian Sea, the same location that the Jews of Phoenicia had earlier been sent.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] After this victory over the Egyptians, Artaxerxes had the city walls destroyed, started a reign of terror, and set about looting all the temples.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Persia gained a significant amount of wealth from this looting.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes also raised high taxes and attempted to weaken Egypt enough that it could never revolt against Persia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] For the 10 years that Persia controlled Egypt, believers in the native religion were persecuted and sacred books were stolen.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Before Artaxerxes returned to Persia, he appointed Pherendares as satrap of Egypt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] With the wealth gained from his reconquering Egypt, Artaxerxes was able to amply reward his mercenaries.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] He then returned to his capital having successfully completed his invasion of Egypt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] After his success in Egypt, Artaxerxes returned to Persia and spent the next few years effectively quelling insurrections in various parts of the Empire so that a few years after his conquest of Egypt, the Persian Empire was firmly under his control.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Egypt remained a part of the Persian Empire from then until Alexander the Great's conquest of Egypt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] After the conquest of Egypt, there were no more revolts or rebellions against Artaxerxes.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mentor and Bagoas, the two generals who had most distinguished themselves in the Egyptian campaign, were advanced to posts of the highest importance.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mentor, who was governor of the entire Asiatic seaboard, was successful in reducing to subjection many of the chiefs who during the recent troubles had rebelled against Persian rule.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the course of a few years, Mentor and his forces were able to bring the whole Asian Mediterranean coast into complete submission and dependence.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas went back to the Persian capital with Artaxerxes, where he took a leading role in the internal administration of the Empire and maintained tranquillity throughout the rest of the Empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] During the last six years of the reign of Artaxerxes III, the Persian Empire was governed by a vigorous and successful government.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian forces in Ionia and Lycia regained control of the Aegean and the Mediterranean Sea and took over much of Athens' former island empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] In response, Isocrates of Athens started giving speeches calling for a 'crusade against the barbarians' but there was not enough strength left in any of the Greek city-states to answer his call.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Although there were no rebellions in the Persian Empire itself, the growing power and territory of Philip II of Macedon in Macedon (against which Demosthenes was in vain warning the Athenians) attracted the attention of Artaxerxes.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] In response, he ordered that Persian influence was to be used to check and constrain the rising power and influence of the Macedonian kingdom.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 340 BC, a Persian force was dispatched to assist the Thracian prince, Cersobleptes, to maintain his independence.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sufficient effective aid was given to the city of Perinthus that the numerous and well-appointed army with which Philip had commenced his siege of the city was compelled to give up the attempt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] By the last year of Artaxerxes' rule, Philip II already had plans in place for an invasion of the Persian Empire, which would crown his career, but the Greeks would not unite with him.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 338 BC Artaxerxes was poisoned by Bagoas with the assistance of a physician.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes III was succeeded by Artaxerxes IV Arses, who before he could act was also poisoned by Bagoas.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas is further said to have killed not only all Arses' children, but many of the other princes of the land.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas then placed Darius III, a nephew of Artaxerxes IV, on the throne.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius III, previously the Satrap of Armenia, personally forced Bagoas to swallow poison.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 334 BC, when Darius was just succeeding in subduing Egypt again, Alexander and his battle-hardened troops invaded Asia Minor.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alexander the Great (Alexander III of Macedon) defeated the Persian armies at Granicus (334 BC), followed by Issus (333 BC), and lastly at Gaugamela (331 BC).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Afterwards, he marched on Susa and Persepolis which surrendered and was destroyed by fire in early 330 BC.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] From Persepolis, Alexander headed north to Pasargadae, where he visited the tomb of Cyrus, the man whom he had heard of from the *Cyropaedia*.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the ensuing chaos created by Alexander's invasion of Persia, Cyrus's tomb was broken into and most of its luxuries were looted.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Alexander reached the tomb, he was horrified by the manner in which it had been treated, and questioned the Magi, putting them on trial.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] By some accounts, Alexander's decision to put the Magi on trial was more an attempt to undermine their influence and display his own power than a show of concern for Cyrus's tomb.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Regardless, Alexander the Great ordered Aristobulus to improve the tomb's condition and restore its interior, showing respect for Cyrus.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] From there he headed to Ecbatana, where Darius III had sought refuge.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius III was taken prisoner by Bessus, his Bactrian satrap and kinsman.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] As Alexander approached, Bessus had his men murder Darius III and then declared himself Darius' successor, as Artaxerxes V, before retreating into Central Asia leaving Darius' body in the road to delay Alexander, who brought it to Persepolis for an honourable funeral.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bessus would then create a coalition of his forces, to create an army to defend against Alexander.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alexander generally kept the original Achaemenid administrative structure, leading some scholars to dub him as "the last of the Achaemenids".
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Upon Alexander's death in 323 BC, his empire was divided among his generals, the Diadochi, resulting in a number of smaller states.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The largest of these, which held sway over the Iranian plateau, was the Seleucid Empire, ruled by Alexander's general Seleucus I Nicator.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Native Iranian rule would be restored by the Parthians of northeastern Iran over the course of the 2nd century BC through the Parthian Empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Several later Persian rulers, forming the *Frataraka* dynasty, are known to have acted as representatives of the Seleucids in the region of Fārs.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] They ruled from the end of the 3rd century BC to the beginning of the 2nd century BC, and Vahbarz or Vādfradād I obtained independence c.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] 150 BC, when Seleucid power waned in the areas of southwestern Persia and the Persian Gulf region.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] During an apparent transitional period, corresponding to the reigns of Vādfradād II and another uncertain king, no titles of authority appeared on the reverse of their coins.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The earlier title *prtrk' zy alhaya* (Frataraka) had disappeared.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under Dārēv I (Darios I) however, the new title of *mlk*, or king, appeared, sometimes with the mention of *prs* (Persis), suggesting that the kings of Persis had become independent rulers.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] When the Parthian Arsacid king Mithridates I (c.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] 171–138 BC) took control of Persis, he left the Persian dynasts in office, known as the Kings of Persis, and they were allowed to continue minting coins with the title of *mlk* ("King").
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid line would also be carried on through the Kingdom of Pontus, based in the Pontus region of northern Asia Minor.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] This Pontic Kingdom, a state of Persian origin, may even have been directly related to Darius I and the Achaemenid dynasty.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was founded by Mithridates I in 281 BC and lasted until its conquest by the Roman Republic in 63 BC.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The kingdom grew to its largest extent under Mithridates VI the Great, who conquered Colchis, Cappadocia, Bithynia, the Greek colonies of the Tauric Chersonesos and for a brief time the Roman province of Asia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Thus, this Persian dynasty managed to survive and prosper in the Hellenistic world while the main Persian Empire had fallen.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Despite Greek influence on the Kingdom of Pontus, Pontics continued to maintain their Achaemenid lineage.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Both the later dynasties of the Parthians and Sasanians would on occasion claim Achaemenid descent.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Recently there has been some corroboration for the Parthian claim to Achaemenid ancestry via the possibility of an inherited disease (neurofibromatosis) demonstrated by the physical descriptions of rulers and from the evidence of familial disease on ancient coinage.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus the Great founded the empire as a multi-state empire, governed from four capital cities: Pasargadae, Babylon, Susa and Ecbatana.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenids allowed a certain amount of regional autonomy in the form of the satrapy system.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] A satrapy was an administrative unit, usually organized on a geographical basis.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] A 'satrap' (governor) was the governor who administered the region, a 'general' supervised military recruitment and ensured order, and a 'state secretary' kept the official records.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The general and the state secretary reported directly to the satrap as well as the central government.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] At differing times, there were between 20 and 30 satrapies.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus the Great created an organized army including the Immortals unit, consisting of 10,000 highly trained soldiers Cyrus also formed an innovative postal system throughout the empire, based on several relay stations called Chapar Khaneh.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Persepolis Administrative Archives provide many insights into the Achaemenid government system.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Found at Persepolis in the 1930s, they are mostly in Elamite; the remains of more than 10,000 of these cuneiform documents have been uncovered.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Aramaic is represented by about 1,000 or more original records.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Only one tablet in Old Persian has been identified so far.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, many seals and seal impressions are found in these Persepolis archives.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] These documents represent administrative activity and flow of data in Persepolis over more than fifty consecutive years (509–457 BC).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian daric was the first gold coin which, along with a similar silver coin, the siglos, introduced the bimetallic monetary standard of the Achaemenids, which has continued until today.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] This was accomplished by Darius I, who reinforced the empire and expanded Persepolis as a ceremonial capital; he revolutionized the economy by placing it on the silver and gold coinage.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius also introduced a regulated and sustainable tax system that was precisely tailored to each satrapy, based on their supposed productivity and their economic potential.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] For instance, Babylon was assessed for the highest amount and for a startling mixture of commodities – 1,000 silver talents, four months' supply of food for the army.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] India was clearly already fabled for its gold; Egypt was known for the wealth of its crops; it was to be the granary of the Persian Empire (as later of Rome's) and was required to provide 120,000 measures of grain in addition to 700 talents of silver.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] This was exclusively a tax levied on subject peoples.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] There is evidence that conquered and rebellious enemies could be sold into slavery.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alongside its other innovations in administration and taxation, the Achaemenids may have been the first government in the ancient Near East to register private slave sales and tax them using an early form of sales tax.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Other accomplishments of Darius' reign included the codification of the *dāta* (a universal legal system which would become the basis of later Iranian law), and the construction of a new capital at Persepolis.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under the Achaemenids, trade was extensive and there was an efficient infrastructure that facilitated the exchange of commodities in the far reaches of the empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Tariffs on trade, along with agriculture and tribute, were major sources of revenue for the empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The satrapies were linked by a 2,500-kilometer highway, the most impressive stretch being the Royal Road from Susa to Sardis, built under the command of Darius I.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] It connected the Iranian Plateau to Central Asia and the Mediterranean.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] It featured stations and caravanserais at specific intervals.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] The relays of mounted couriers (the angarium) could reach the remotest of areas in fifteen days.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus observes that "there is nothing in the world that travels faster than these Persian couriers.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following Alexander's conquests, this highway allowed for the spread of cultural syncretic fusions like Greco-Buddhism into Central Asia and China, as well as empires like the Kushan, Indo-Greek and Parthian to profit from trade between East and West.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p01] This route was greatly rehabilitated and formalized during the Abbasid Caliphate, during which it developed into a major component of the famed Silk Road.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Despite its humble origins in Persis, the empire reached an enormous size under the leadership of Cyrus the Great.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus created a multi-state empire where he allowed regional rulers, satraps, to rule as his proxy over a certain designated area of his empire called a satrapy.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The basic rule of governance was based upon loyalty and obedience of each satrapy to the central power, or the king, and compliance with tax laws.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus managed to create a strong land army, using it to advance in his campaigns in Babylonia, Lydia, and Asia Minor, which after his death was used by his son Cambyses II, in Egypt against Psamtik III.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus would die battling a local Iranian insurgency in the empire, before he could have a chance to develop a naval force.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] That task would fall to Darius I, who would officially give Persians their own royal navy to allow them to engage their enemies on multiple seas of this vast empire, from the Black Sea and the Aegean Sea, to the Persian Gulf, Ionian Sea and the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid infantry consisted of three groups: the Immortals, the Sparabara, and the Takabara, though in the later years of the Achaemenid Empire, a fourth group, the Cardaces, were introduced.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Immortals were described by Herodotus as being heavy infantry, led by Hydarnes II, that were kept constantly at a strength of exactly 10,000 men.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] He claimed that the unit's name stemmed from the custom that every killed, seriously wounded, or sick member was immediately replaced with a new one, maintaining the numbers and cohesion of the unit.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] They had wicker shields, short spears, swords or large daggers, and bow and arrows.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Underneath their robes they wore scale armour coats.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The spear counterbalances of the common soldiery were of silver; to differentiate commanding ranks, the officers' spear butt-spikes were golden.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Surviving Achaemenid colored glazed bricks and carved reliefs represent the Immortals as wearing elaborate robes, hoop earrings and gold jewellery, though these garments and accessories were most likely worn only for ceremonial occasions.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Sparabara were usually the first to engage in hand-to-hand combat with the enemy.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although not much is known about them today, it is believed that they were the backbone of the Persian army who formed a shield wall and used their two-metre-long spears to protect more vulnerable troops such as archers from the enemy.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Sparabara were taken from the full members of Persian society, were trained from childhood to be soldiers and when not called out to fight on campaigns in distant lands they practised hunting on the vast plains of Persia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, when all was quiet and the *Pax Persica* held true, the Sparabara returned to normal life farming the land and grazing their herds.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Because of this, they lacked true professional quality on the battlefield, yet they were well trained and courageous to the point of holding the line in most situations long enough for a counter-attack.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] They were armoured with quilted linen and carried large rectangular wicker shields as a form of light maneuverable defence.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] This, however, left them at a severe disadvantage against heavily armoured opponents such as the hoplite, and their two-metre-long spear was not able to give the Sparabara ample range to plausibly engage a trained phalanx.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The wicker shields were able to effectively stop arrows but not strong enough to protect the soldier from spears.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, the Sparabara could deal with most other infantry, including trained units from the East.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenids relied heavily on archery.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Major contributing nations were the Scythians, Medes, Persians, and the Elamites.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The composite bow was used by the Persians and Medes, who adopted it from the Scythians and transmitted it to other nations, including the Greeks.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid armies typically used socketed, three-bladed (also known as trilobate or Scythian) arrowheads.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] These arrowheads were cast from leaded tin-bronze, which made them amenable to mass-production unlike the wrought iron arrowheads of the period that had to be individually forged.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Takabara were a rare unit who were a tough type of peltasts.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] They tended to fight with their own native weapons which would have included a crescent-shaped light wickerwork shield and axes as well as light linen cloth and leather.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Takabara were recruited from territories that incorporated modern Iran.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian cavalry was crucial for conquering nations and maintained its importance in the Achaemenid army to the last days of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The cavalry was separated into four groups.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariot archers, horse cavalry, the camel cavalry, and the war elephants.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] In the later years of the Achaemenid Empire, the chariot archer had become merely a ceremonial part of the Persian army, yet in the early years of the Empire, their use was widespread.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariot archers were armed with lances, bows, arrows, swords, and scale armour.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The horses were also suited with scale armour similar to scale armour of the Sassanian cataphracts.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariots would contain imperial symbols and decorations.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The horses used by the Achaemenids for cavalry were often suited with scale armour, like most cavalry units.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The riders often had the same armour as Infantry units, wicker shields, short spears, swords or large daggers, bow and arrow, and scale armour coats.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The camel cavalry was different, because the camels and sometimes the riders, were provided little protection against enemies, yet when they were offered protection, they would have lances, swords, bow, arrow, and scale armour.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The camel cavalry was first introduced into the Persian army by Cyrus the Great, at the Battle of Thymbra.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The elephant was most likely introduced into the Persian army by Darius I after his conquest of the Indus Valley.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Elephants may have been used in Greek campaigns by Darius and Xerxes I, but Greek accounts only mention 15 of them being used at the Battle of Gaugamela.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Since its foundation by Cyrus, the Persian empire had been primarily a land empire with a strong army but void of any actual naval forces.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] By the 5th century BC, this was to change, as the empire came across Greek and Egyptian forces, each with their own maritime traditions and capabilities.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius I was the first Achaemenid king to invest in a Persian fleet.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Even by then no true "imperial navy" had existed either in Greece or Egypt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Persia would become the first empire, under Darius, to inaugurate and deploy the first regular imperial navy.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Despite this achievement, the personnel for the imperial navy would not come from Iran, but were often Phoenicians (mostly from Sidon), Egyptians and Greeks chosen by Darius the Great to operate the empire's combat vessels.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] At first the ships were built in Sidon by the Phoenicians; the first Achaemenid ships measured about 40 meters in length and 6 meters in width, able to transport up to 300 Persian troops at any one trip.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Soon, other states of the empire were constructing their own ships, each incorporating slight local preferences.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships eventually found their way to the Persian Gulf and Persian naval forces laid the foundation for a strong Persian maritime presence there.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Persians also had ships often of a capacity 100 to 200 troops patrolling the empire's various rivers including the Karun, Tigris and Nile in the west, as well as the Indus.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid navy established bases located along the Karun, and in Bahrain, Oman, and Yemen.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian fleet was not only used for peace-keeping purposes along the Karun but also opened the door to trade with India via the Persian Gulf.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius's navy was in many ways a world power at the time, but it would be Artaxerxes II who in the summer of 397 BC would build a formidable navy, as part of a rearmament which would lead to his decisive victory at Knidos in 394 BC, re-establishing Achaemenid power in Ionia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Artaxerxes II would also use his navy to later on quell a rebellion in Egypt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The construction material of choice was wood, but some armoured Achaemenid ships had metallic blades on the front, often meant to slice enemy ships using the ship's momentum.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Naval ships were also equipped with hooks on the side to grab enemy ships, or to negotiate their position.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships were propelled by sails or manpower.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships the Persians created were unique.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] As far as maritime engagement, the ships were equipped with two mangonels that would launch projectiles such as stones, or flammable substances.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Xenophon describes his eyewitness account of a massive military bridge created by joining 37 Persian ships across the Tigris.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persians used each boat's buoyancy to support a connected bridge above which supply could be transferred.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus also gives many accounts of the Persians using ships to build bridges.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius I, in an attempt to subdue the Scythian horsemen north of the Black Sea, crossed over at the Bosphorus, using an enormous bridge made by connecting Achaemenid boats, then marched up to the Danube, crossing it by means of a second boat bridge.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The bridge over the Bosphorus essentially connected the nearest tip of Asia to Europe, encompassing at least some 1000 meters of open water if not more.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Years later, a similar boat bridge would be constructed by Xerxes I, in his invasion of Greece.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although the Persians failed to capture the Greek city-states completely, the tradition of maritime involvement was carried down by the Persian kings, most notably Artaxerxes II.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Years later, when Alexander invaded Persia and during his advancement into India, he took a page from the Persian art of war, by having Hephaestion and Perdiccas construct a similar boat-bridge at the Indus river in India in the spring of 327 BC.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] They all had the same trilingual inscription (DPh inscription).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] During the reign of Cyrus II and Darius I, and as long as the seat of government was still at Susa in Elam, the language of the chancellery was Elamite.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] This is primarily attested in the Persepolis fortification and treasury tablets that reveal details of the day-to-day functioning of the empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] In the grand rock-face inscriptions of the kings, the Elamite texts are always accompanied by Akkadian (Babylonian dialect) and Old Persian inscriptions, and it appears that in these cases that the Elamite texts are translations of the Old Persian ones.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] It is then likely that although Elamite was used by the capital government in Susa, it was not a standardized language of government everywhere in the empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The use of Elamite is not attested after 458 BC.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Following the conquest of Mesopotamia, the Aramaic language (as used in that territory) was adopted as a "vehicle for written communication between the different regions of the vast empire with its different peoples and languages.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] In 1955, Richard Frye questioned the classification of Imperial Aramaic as an official language, noting that no surviving edict expressly and unambiguously accorded that status to any particular language.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Frye reclassifies Imperial Aramaic as the *lingua franca* of the Achaemenid empire, suggesting that the use of Aramaic language in Achaemenid empire was more widespread than generally thought.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Many centuries after the fall of the empire, Aramaic script and—as ideograms—Aramaic vocabulary would survive as the essential characteristics of the Pahlavi writing system.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although Old Persian also appears on some seals and art objects, that language is attested primarily in the Achaemenid inscriptions of Western Iran, suggesting then that Old Persian was the common language of that region.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] When the occasion demanded, Achaemenid administrative correspondence was conducted in Greek, making it a widely used bureaucratic language.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Even though the Achaemenids had extensive contacts with the Greeks and vice versa, and had conquered many of the Greek-speaking areas both in Europe and Asia Minor during different periods of the empire, the native Old Iranian sources provide no indication of Greek linguistic influence.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, there is plenty of evidence (in addition to the accounts of Herodotus) that Greeks, apart from being deployed and employed in the core regions of the empire, also evidently lived and worked in the heartland of the Achaemenid Empire, namely Iran.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] For example, Greeks were part of the various ethnicities that constructed Darius' palace in Susa, apart from the Greek inscriptions found nearby there, and one short Persepolis tablet written in Greek.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus mentions that the Persians were invited to great birthday feasts (Herodotus, *Histories* 8), which would be followed by many desserts, a treat which they reproached the Greeks for omitting from their meals.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] He also observed that the Persians drank wine in large quantities and used it even for counsel, deliberating on important affairs when drunk, and deciding the next day, when sober, whether to act on the decision or set it aside.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Religious toleration has been described as a "remarkable feature" of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Hebrew Bible reports that Persian king Cyrus the Great released the Jewish people from the Babylonian captivity in 539–530 BC and permitted them to return to their homeland.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus the Great assisted in the restoration of the sacred places of various cities, including to rebuild the Israelites’ Temple in Jerusalem.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] It was during the Achaemenid period that Zoroastrianism reached southwestern Iran, where it came to be accepted by the rulers and through them became a defining element of Persian culture.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The religion was not only accompanied by a formalization of the concepts and divinities of the traditional Iranian pantheon but also introduced several novel ideas, including that of free will.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Mithra was worshipped in the Empire; his temples and symbols were the most widespread, most people bore names related to him and most festivals were dedicated to him.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] During the reign of Artaxerxes I and Darius II, the Greek historian Herodotus wrote: "[the Persians] have no images of the gods, no temples nor altars, and consider the use of them a sign of folly.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] This comes, I think, from their not believing the gods to have the same nature with men, as the Greeks imagine." He claims the Persians offer sacrifice to: "the sun and moon, to the earth, to fire, to water, and to the winds.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] These are the only gods whose worship has come down to them from ancient times.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] At a later period, they began the worship of Urania, which they borrowed from the Arabians and Assyrians.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Babylonian scholar and priest Berosus records—although writing over seventy years after the reign of Artaxerxes II—that the emperor had been the first to make cult statues of divinities and have them placed in temples in many of the major cities of the empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Berosus also substantiates Herodotus when he says the Persians knew of no images of gods until Artaxerxes II erected those images.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] On the means of sacrifice, Herodotus adds "they raise no altar, light no fire, pour no libations." Herodotus also observed that "no prayer or offering can be made without a magus present".
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The position of women in the Achaemenid Empire varied depending on the culture to which they belonged and therefore differed by region.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The hierarchy of royal women at the Persian court was ranked as follows: the king's mother, then the queen, the king's daughters, the king's concubines, and the other women of the royal palace.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The king normally married a female member of the royal family or a Persian noblewoman related to a satrap or another important Persian man; it was permitted for members of the royal family to marry relatives, but there is no evidence for marriage between closer family members than half-siblings.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The king's concubines were often either slaves, sometimes prisoners of war, or foreign princesses, whom the king did not marry because they were foreigners, and whose children did not have the right to inherit the throne.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Greek sources accuse the king of having hundreds of concubines secluded in a harem.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] There is no archeological evidence supporting the existence of a harem, or the seclusion of women from contact with men, at the Persian court.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The royal women joined the king at breakfast and dinner and accompanied him on his journeys.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] They may have participated in the royal hunt, as well as during the royal banquets.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus relates how the Persian envoys at the Macedonian court demanded the presence of women during a banquet because it was the custom for women to participate in the banquets in their own country.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The queen may have attended the king's audience, and archeological evidence shows that she gave her own audiences, at least for female supplicants.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal women and noblewomen at court could travel on their own, accompanied by both male and female staff, own and manage their own fortune, land, and business.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Depictions of Persian women show them with long dresses and veils which did not cover their faces or their hair, only flowing down over their neck at the back of the head as an ornament.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic Achaemenid women were given an education in subjects that did not appear compatible with seclusions, such as horsemanship and archery.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic women held and managed vast estates and workshops and employed large numbers of servants and professional laborers.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic women do not seem to have lived in seclusion from men, since it is known that they appeared in public and traveled with their husbands, participated in hunting and in feasts.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chief wife of a royal or aristocratic man did not live in seclusion, as it is clearly stated that wives customarily accompanied their husbands at dinner banquets.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] They left the banquet when the "women entertainers" came in and the men began "merrymaking".
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] No woman ever ruled the Achaemenid Empire, as monarch or as regent, but some queen's consorts are known to have had influence over the affairs of state, notably Atossa and Parysatis.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] There is not evidence of any women being employed as an official in the administration or within religious service; however, there are plenty of archeological evidence of women being employed as free labourers in Persepolis, where they worked alongside men.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Women could be employed as the leaders of their workforce, known by the title *arraššara pašabena*, which were then given a higher salary than the male workers of their workforce.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Female laborers were given less than men.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Qualified workers within the crafts were given equal pay regardless of their sex.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Women are abundant in religious context in the cuneiform sources from late Achaemenid and Hellenistic Babylon.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid architecture included large cities, temples, palaces, and mausolea such as the Tomb of Cyrus the Great.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The quintessential feature of its architecture was its eclectic nature, with elements of Median, Assyrian, and Asiatic Greek all incorporated, yet maintaining a unique Persian identity seen in the finished products.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Its influence pervades the regions ruled by the Achaemenids, from the Mediterranean shores to India, especially with its emphasis on monumental stone-cut design and gardens subdivided by water-courses.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid art includes frieze reliefs, metalwork such as the Oxus Treasure, decoration of palaces, glazed brick masonry, fine craftsmanship (masonry, carpentry, etc.), and gardening.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although the Persians drew artists from all corners of their empire, incorporating their styles and techniques, they did not merely produce a combination of styles, but a synthesis of a new, unique Persian style.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] One of the most remarkable examples of both Achaemenid architecture and art is the grand palace of Persepolis, and its detailed workmanship, coupled with its grand scale.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Many Achaemenid rulers built tombs for themselves.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The most famous, Naqsh-e Rostam, is an ancient necropolis located about 12 km north-west of Persepolis, with the tombs of four of the kings of the dynasty are carved in this mountain: Darius I, Xerxes I, Artaxerxes I and Darius II.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Other kings constructed their own tombs elsewhere.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Artaxerxes II and Artaxerxes III preferred to carve their tombs beside their spring capital Persepolis.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The left tomb belongs to Artaxerxes II and the right tomb belongs to Artaxerxes III, the last Achaemenid king to have a tomb.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The tomb of the founder of the Achaemenid dynasty, Cyrus the Great, was built in Pasargadae (now a world heritage site).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire has been referred to as the first “world empire” as it contained in the words of Persian kings “many people and many languages”.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The diverse groups which made up the empire enjoyed a great deal of legal and cultural autonomy.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire has also left a lasting impression on the heritage and cultural identity of Asia and the Middle East, and influenced the development and structure of future empires.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] In fact, the Greeks, and later on the Romans, adopted the best features of the Persian method of governing an empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian model of governance was particularly formative in the expansion and maintenance of the Abbasid Caliphate, whose rule is widely considered the period of the Islamic Golden Age.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire is noted in Western history as the antagonist of the Greek city-states during the Greco-Persian Wars and for the emancipation of the Jewish exiles in Babylon.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The historical mark of the empire went far beyond its territorial and military influences and included cultural, social, technological and religious influences as well.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] For example, many Athenians adopted Achaemenid customs in their daily lives in a reciprocal cultural exchange, some being employed by or allied to the Persian kings.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The impact of the Edict of Cyrus is mentioned in Judeo-Christian texts, and the empire was instrumental in the spread of Zoroastrianism as far east as China.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] The empire also set the tone for the politics, heritage and history of Iran (also known as Persia).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/achaemenid-empire-p02] Hegel in his work *The Philosophy of History* introduces the Persian Empire as the "first empire that passed away" and its people as the "first historical people" in history.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/adikhalamani] Adikhalamani's name is known only from inscriptions at the temple complex of Philae.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/adikhalamani] Although no burial for Adikhalamani can be securely identified, he is conventionally attributed either Beg.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/adikhalamani] N 9, both located in Meroë and dating to the approximate time of Adikhalamani's reign.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/adikhalamani] N 8 preserves the fragmentary name "(...)mr(...)t" and Beg.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/adikhalamani] László Török (2015) suggested that Tabirqo was a "funerary name" of Adikhalamani and that (...)mr(...)t was a distinct succeeding king.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/adikhalamani] Josefine Kuckertz (2021) instead proposed that Adikhalamani and (...)mr(...)t were the same king and that Tabirqo was a distinct succeeding king.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/adikhalamani] If Kuckertz's identification is accepted, Adikhalamani was the husband of Nahirqo, whose name is recorded in Beg.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/adikhalamani] N 8 and who later ruled as the first queen regnant of Kush.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/adikhalamani] Adikhalamani is believed to have been contemporary with an Egyptian revolt dated to ca.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/adikhalamani] During this revolt a ruler, Horwennefer took control of Thebes and revolted against Ptolemy IV Philopator.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/adikhalamani] 186 BCE when Ankhwennefer (his successor or more likely Horwennefer with a different nomen) was captured and executed.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The **Kingdom of Kush**, also known as the **Kushite Empire**, or simply **Kush**, was an ancient kingdom in Nubia, centered along the Nile Valley in what is now Sudan.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The region of Nubia was an early cradle of civilization, producing several complex societies that engaged in trade and industry.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The city-state of Kerma emerged as the dominant political force between 2450 and 1450 BC, controlling the Nile Valley between the first and fourth cataracts, an area as large as Egypt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The Egyptians were the first to identify Kerma as "Kush" probably from the indigenous ethnonym "Kasu", and over the next several centuries the two civilizations engaged in intermittent warfare, trade, and cultural exchange.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Much of Nubia came under Egyptian rule during the New Kingdom period (1550–1070 BC).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Following Egypt's disintegration amid the Late Bronze Age collapse, the Kushites reestablished a kingdom in Napata (now modern Karima, Sudan).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] In the 8th century BC, King Kashta ("the Kushite") peacefully became king of Upper Egypt, while his daughter, Amenirdis, was appointed as divine adoratrice of Amun in Thebes.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] His successor Piye invaded Lower Egypt, establishing the Kushite-ruled Twenty-fifth Dynasty.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Piye's daughter, Shepenupet II, was also appointed divine adoratrice of Amun.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The monarchs of Kush ruled Egypt for over a century until the Assyrian conquest, being dethroned by the Assyrian kings Esarhaddon and Ashurbanipal in the mid-7th century BC.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Following the severing of ties with Egypt, the Kushite imperial capital was located at Meroë, during which time it was known by the Greeks as Aethiopia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The northernmost part of Nubia was occupied from the 3rd century BC to the 3rd century AD, first by the Ptolemaic Kingdom and then by the Roman Empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] At the end of this 600-year period, the territory, known in the Greco-Roman world as Dodekaschoinos, was taken back by the Kushite king Yesebokheamani.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The kingdom of Kush persisted as a major regional power until the 4th century AD, when it weakened and disintegrated amid worsening climatic conditions, internal rebellions, and foreign invasions—notably by the Noba people, who introduced the Nubian languages and gave their name to Nubia itself.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] While the Kushites were occupied by war with the Noba and the Blemmyes, the Aksumites took the opportunity to capture Meroë and loot its gold.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Negus Ezana then took on the title of "King of Ethiopia", a practice which would last into the modern period and was recorded in inscriptions found in both Axum and Meroe.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Although the Aksumite presence was likely short-lived, it prompted the dissolution of the Kushite kingdom into the three polities of Nobatia, Makuria and Alodia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The Kingdom of Alodia subsequently gained control of the southern territory of the former Meroitic empire, including parts of Eritrea.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Long overshadowed by Egypt, archaeological discoveries since the late 20th century have revealed Kush to be an advanced civilization.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The Kushites had their own unique language and script; maintained a complex economy based on trade and industry; mastered archery; and developed a complex, urban society with uniquely high levels of female participation.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The native name of the kingdom was recorded in Egyptian as **kꜣš**, likely pronounced [kuɫuʃ] or [kuʔuʃ] in Middle Egyptian, when the term was first used for Nubia, based on the New Kingdom-era Assyrian and Babylonian Akkadian transliteration of the genitive *kūsi*.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] It is also an ethnic term for the native population who initiated the kingdom of Kush.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The term is also displayed in the names of Kushite persons, such as King Kashta (a transcription of *kꜣš-tꜣ* "(one from) the land of Kush").
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Geographically, Kush referred to the region south of the first cataract in general.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Kush also was the home of the rulers of the 25th Dynasty.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The name *Kush*, since at least the time of Josephus, has been connected with the biblical character Cush, in the Hebrew Bible (Hebrew: כּוּשׁ), son of Ham (Genesis 10:6).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Ham had four sons named: Cush, Put, Canaan, and Mizraim (Hebrew name for Egypt).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] According to the Bible, Nimrod, a son of Cush, was the founder and king of Babylon, Erech, Akkad and Calneh, in Shinar (Gen 10:10).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The Bible also makes reference to someone named Cush who is a Benjamite (Psalms 7:1, KJV).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] In Ancient Greek sources Kush was known as *Kous* (Κους) or *Aethiopia* (Αἰθιοπία).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The Nabta Playa civilization emerged in Nubia around 7500 BC.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Megaliths discovered at Nabta Playa are early examples of what seems to be one of the world's first astronomical devices, predating Stonehenge by almost 2,000 years.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Archaeological discoveries reveal that these New Stone Age peoples seem to have lived more organized lives than their contemporaries nearer to and in the Nile Valley.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The people of Nabta Playa had villages with 'planned' layouts, with deep wells that held water year-round.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The A-Group was a civilization in Nubia that lasted from the 4th millennium BC, reached its climax at c.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The Kerma culture was a civilization centered in Kerma, Sudan.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] It flourished from around 2500 BC to 1500 BC in ancient Nubia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The Kerma culture was based in the southern part of Nubia, or "Upper Nubia" (in parts of present-day northern and central Sudan), and later extended its reach northward into Lower Nubia and the border of Egypt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The polity seems to have been one of several Nile Valley states during the Middle Kingdom of Egypt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] In the Kingdom of Kerma's latest phase, lasting from about 1700–1500 BC, it absorbed the Sudanese kingdom of Saï and became a sizable, populous empire rivaling Egypt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Doukki Gel was a settlement near Kerma, Doukki Gel was inhabited between 1800 BC to 400 AD and was occupied by a coalition of African rulers from the south around 1700 BC during the Classical Kerma period, and later by Ancient Egyptian and Nubian officials during the new kingdom period.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The settlement is located less than 1 kilometre (0.62 mi) south of the city of Kerma, and shows distinctive Sub Saharan influences architecturally distinct from Kerma with more rounded structures.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Mentuhotep II, the 21st century BC founder of the Middle Kingdom, is recorded to have undertaken campaigns against Kush in the 29th and 31st years of his reign.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] This is the earliest Egyptian reference to *Kush*; the Nubian region had gone by other names in the Old Kingdom.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Under Thutmose I, Egypt made several campaigns south.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The Egyptians ruled Kush in the New kingdom beginning when the Egyptian King Thutmose I occupied Kush and destroyed its capital, Kerma.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] This eventually resulted in their annexation of Nubia c.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Around 1500 BC, Nubia was absorbed into the New Kingdom of Egypt, but rebellions continued for centuries.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] After the conquest, Kerma culture was increasingly Egyptianized, yet rebellions continued for 220 years until c.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Nubia nevertheless became a key province of the New Kingdom, economically, politically, and spiritually.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Indeed, major pharaonic ceremonies were held at Jebel Barkal near Napata.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] As an Egyptian colony from the 16th century BC, Nubia ("Kush") was governed by an Egyptian Viceroy of Kush.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Resistance to the early eighteenth Dynasty Egyptian rule by neighboring Kush is evidenced in the writings of Ahmose, son of Ebana, an Egyptian warrior who served under Nebpehtrya Ahmose (1539–1514 BC), Djeserkara Amenhotep I (1514–1493 BC), and Aakheperkara Thutmose I (1493–1481 BC).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] At the end of the Second Intermediate Period (mid-sixteenth century BC), Egypt faced the twin existential threats—the Hyksos in the North and the Kushites in the South.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Taken from the autobiographical inscriptions on the walls of his tomb-chapel, the Egyptians undertook campaigns to defeat Kush and conquer Nubia under the rule of Amenhotep I (1514–1493 BC).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] In Ahmose's writings, the Kushites are described as archers, "Now after his Majesty had slain the Bedoin of Asia, he sailed upstream to Upper Nubia to destroy the Nubian bowmen." The tomb writings contain two other references to the Nubian bowmen of Kush.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] By 1200 BC, Egyptian involvement in the Dongola Reach was nonexistent.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Egypt's international prestige had declined considerably towards the end of the Third Intermediate Period.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Its historical allies, the inhabitants of Canaan, had fallen to the Middle Assyrian Empire (1365–1020 BC), and then the resurgent Neo-Assyrian Empire (935–605 BC).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The Assyrians, from the tenth century BC onwards, had once more expanded from northern Mesopotamia, and conquered a vast empire, including the whole of the Near East, and much of Anatolia, the eastern Mediterranean, the Caucasus and early Iron Age Iran.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] According to Josephus Flavius, the biblical Moses led the Egyptian army in a siege of the Kushite city of Meroe.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] To end the siege Princess Tharbis was given to Moses as a (diplomatic) bride, and thus the Egyptian army retreated back to Egypt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] With the disintegration of the New Kingdom around 1070 BC, *Kush* became an independent kingdom centered at Napata in modern northern Sudan.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] This more-Egyptianized "Kingdom of Kush" emerged, possibly from Kerma, and regained the region's independence from Egypt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The extent of cultural/political continuity between the Kerma culture and the chronologically succeeding Kingdom of Kush is difficult to determine.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The latter polity began to emerge around 1000 BC, 500 years after the end of the Kingdom of Kerma.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The first Kushite king known by name was Alara, who ruled somewhere between 800 and 760 BC.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] No contemporary inscriptions of him exist.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] He was first mentioned in the funerary stela of his daughter Tabiry, the wife of king Piye.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Later royal inscriptions remember Alara as the founder of the dynasty, some calling him "chieftain", others "king".
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] A 7th century inscription claimed that his sister was the grandmother of king Taharqo.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] An inscription of the 5th century king Amanineteyerike remembered Alara's reign as long and successful.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Alara was probably buried at el-Kurru, although there exists no inscription to identify his tomb.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] It has been proposed that it was Alara who turned Kush from a chiefdom to an Egyptianized kingdom centered around the cult of Amun.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Alara's successor Kashta extended Kushite control north to Elephantine and Thebes in Upper Egypt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Kashta's successor Piye seized control of Lower Egypt around 727 BC.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Piye's Victory Stela, celebrating these campaigns between 728 and 716 BC, was found in the Amun temple at Jebel Barkal.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] He invaded an Egypt fragmented into four kingdoms, ruled by King Peftjauawybast, King Nimlot, King Iuput II, and King Osorkon IV.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Why the Kushites chose to enter Egypt at this crucial point of foreign domination is subject to debate.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Archaeologist Timothy Kendall offers his own hypotheses, connecting it to a claim of legitimacy associated with Jebel Barkal.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Kendall cites the Victory Stele of Piye at Jebel Barkal, which states that "Amun of Napata granted me to be ruler of every foreign country", and "Amun in Thebes granted me to be ruler of the Black Land (Kmt)".
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] According to Kendall, "foreign lands" in this regard seems to include Lower Egypt while "Kmt" seems to refer to a united Upper Egypt and Nubia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Piye's successor, Shabataka, defeated the Saite kings of northern Egypt between 711 and 710 BC and installed himself as king in Memphis.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] He then suppoted another rebellion against the Assyrians in the Levant, but this met with failure.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] He later established ties with Sargon II of the Neo-Assyrian Empire, even sending him Iamani, the rebel ruler of Ashsod as a placatory gesture after Iamani had fled into Egypt .
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] However the regions in the southern Levant claimed by Shabataka were seen by Assyria as under their dominion, and imperial ambitions of both the Mesopotamian based Neo-Assyrian Empire and Kushite Empire made war with the 25th dynasty inevitable.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] In 701 BC, Taharqa and his army aided Judah and King Hezekiah in withstanding a siege by King Sennacherib of the Assyrians (2 Kings 19:9; Isaiah 37:9).
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] There are various theories (Taharqa's army, disease, divine intervention, Hezekiah's surrender or agreeing to pay tribute) as to why the Assyrians failed to take the city.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The power of the 25th Dynasty reached a climax under Taharqa.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The Nile valley empire was as large as it had been since the New Kingdom.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] New prosperity revived Egyptian culture.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Religion, the arts, and architecture were restored to their glorious Old, Middle, and New Kingdom forms.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The Kushite pharaohs built or restored temples and monuments throughout the Nile valley, including Memphis, Karnak, Kawa, and Jebel Barkal.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] It was during the 25th dynasty that the Nile valley saw the first widespread construction of pyramids (many in modern Sudan) since the Middle Kingdom.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The Kushites developed their own script, the Meroitic alphabet, which was influenced by Egyptian writing systems c.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] 700–600 BC, although it appears to have been wholly confined to the royal court and major temples.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Taharqa and his Judean allies initially held the Assyrians at Ashkelon when war broke out in 674 BC.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The relatively small Assyrian force had first defeafed Canaanite, Aramean and Arab tribes in the region and then immediately marched at great speed on Ashkelon, leaving them exhausted and unable to advance further.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] However, in 671 BC, the Assyrian King Esarhaddon started the Assyrian conquest of Egypt with a larger and better prepared force.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The Assyrians advanced rapidly and decisively.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Memphis was taken, and Taharqa fled back to Nubia, while his heir and other family members were taken to the Assyrian capital Nineveh as prisoners.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Esarhaddon boasted how he "deported all Aethiopians from Egypt, leaving not one to pay homage to me".
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] However, the native Egyptian vassal rulers installed by Esarhaddon as puppets were unable to effectively retain full control of the entire country, and Taharqa was able to regain control of Memphis.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Esarhaddon's 669 BC campaign to once more eject Taharqa was abandoned when Esarhaddon died in the northern Assyrian city of Harran on the way to Egypt, leaving Esarhaddon's successor Ashurbanipal the task.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] He defeated Taharqa, driving his forces back into Nubia, and Taharqa died in Napata soon after in 664 BC.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Taharqa's successor, Tantamani sailed north from Napata, through Elephantine, and to Thebes with a large army, where he was "ritually installed as the king of Egypt".
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] From Thebes, Tantamani began his attempt at reconquest and regained control of a part of southern Egypt as far as Memphis from the native Egyptian puppet rulers installed by the Assyrians.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Tantamani's dream stele states that he restored order from the chaos, where royal temples and cults were not being maintained.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] After defeating Sais and killing Assyria's vassal, Necho I, in Memphis, "some local dynasts formally surrendered, while others withdrew to their fortresses".
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Tantamani proceeded north of Memphis, invading Lower Egypt and, besieged cities in the Delta, a number of which surrendered to him.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The Assyrians, who had maintained only a small military presence in the north, then sent a large army southwards in 663 BC.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Tantamani was decisively routed, and the Assyrian army sacked Thebes to such an extent it never truly recovered.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Tantamani was chased back to Nubia, but he continued to try and assert control over Upper Egypt until c.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] At this date, a native Egyptian ruler, Psamtik I son of Necho, placed on the throne as a vassal of Ashurbanipal, took control of Thebes.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The last links between Kush and Upper Egypt were severed after hostilities with the Saite kings in the 590s BC.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Kushite civilization continued for several centuries.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Herodotus mentioned an invasion of Kush by the Achaemenid ruler Cambyses (c.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] By some accounts Cambyses succeeded in occupying the area between the first and second Nile cataract, however Herodotus mentions that "his expedition failed miserably in the desert." Achaemenid inscriptions from both Egypt and Iran include Kush as part of the Achaemenid empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] For example, the DNa inscription of Darius I (r.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] 522–486 BC) on his tomb at Naqsh-e Rustam mentions *Kūšīyā* (Old Persian cuneiform: 𐎤𐎢𐏁𐎡𐎹𐎠, pronounced *Kūshīyā*) among the territories being "ruled over" by the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] From around 425–300 BC, beginning under the rule of king Amannote-erike, Kush saw a series of kings who revitalized older practices such as the erection of royal steles or royal statues.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] It was likely also in this period when several older pyramids, among them that of Taharqo, were enlarged.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The stele of king Harsiotef, who from around 400 BC ruled for at least 35 years, reports how he fought a multitude of campaigns against enemies ranging from Meroe in the south to Lower Nubia in the north while also donating to temples throughout Kush.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] 325) waged several wars against nomad groups and again in Lower Nubia.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Nastasen was the last king to be buried at Nuri.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] His successors built six pyramids at Jebel Barkal and two in the old necropolis of el-Kurru, although the lack of inscriptions prevents identifying their occupants.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] It seems likely that this was a time of unrest and conflict within the royal elite.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Aspelta moved the capital to Meroë, considerably farther south than Napata, possibly c.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] 591 BC, just after the sack of Napata by Psamtik II.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Martin Meredith states the Kushite rulers chose Meroë, between the Fifth and Sixth Cataracts, because it was on the fringe of the summer rainfall belt, and the area was rich in iron ore and hardwood for iron working.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The location also afforded access to trade routes to the Red Sea.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The Kush traded iron products with the Romans, in addition to gold, ivory and slaves.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The Butana plain was stripped of its forests, leaving behind slag piles.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] In about 300 BC, the move to Meroë was made more complete when the monarchs began to be buried there, instead of at Napata.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] One theory is that this represents the monarchs breaking away from the power of the priests at Napata.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] According to Diodorus Siculus, Kushite king Ergamenes defied the priests and had them slaughtered.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] This story may refer to the first ruler to be buried at Meroë with a similar name such as Arqamani, who ruled many years after the royal cemetery was opened at Meroë.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] During this same period, the Kushite authority may have extended some 1,500 km along the Nile River valley from the Egyptian frontier in the north to areas far south of modern Khartoum and probably also substantial territories to the east and west.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] There is some record of conflict between the Kushites and Ptolemaic Egypt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] 283–246 BC) sent an army to Nubia, and defeated the Kingdom of Kush, annexing to Egypt the area later known as Triakontaschoinos.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] In addition, there was a serious revolt at the end of the reign of Ptolemy IV, around 204 BC, and the Kushites likely tried to interfere in Ptolemaic affairs.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] It has been suggested that this led to Ptolemy V defacing the name of Arqamani on inscriptions at Philae.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Dynastic struggles led to the Ptolemies abandoning the area, so "the Kushites reasserted their control...with Qasr Ibrim occupied" (by the Kushites) and other locations perhaps garrisoned.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] According to Welsby, after the Romans assumed control of Egypt, they negotiated with the Kushites at Philae and drew the southern border of Roman Egypt at Aswan.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Theodor Mommsen and Welsby state the Kingdom of Kush became a client Kingdom, which was similar to the situation under Ptolemaic rule of Egypt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Kushite ambition and excessive Roman taxation are two theories for a revolt that was supported by Kushite armies.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The ancient historians, Strabo and Pliny, give accounts of the conflict with Roman Egypt.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Strabo describes a war with the Romans in the first century BC.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] According to Strabo, the Kushites "sacked Aswan with an army of 30,000 men and destroyed imperial statues...at Philae." A "fine over-life-size bronze head of the emperor Augustus" was found buried in Meroe in front of a temple.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] After the initial victories of Kandake (or "Candace") Amanirenas against Roman Egypt, the Kushites were defeated and Napata sacked.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Remarkably, the destruction of the capital of Napata was not a crippling blow to the Kushites and did not frighten Candace enough to prevent her from again engaging in combat with the Roman military.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] In 22 BC, a large Kushite force moved northward with intention of attacking Qasr Ibrim.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Alerted to the advance, Gaius Petronius, prefect of Roman Egypt, again marched south and managed to reach Qasr Ibrim and bolster its defenses before the invading Kushites arrived.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Welsby states after a Kushite attack on Primis (Qasr Ibrim), the Kushites sent ambassadors to negotiate a peace settlement with Petronius.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The Kushites succeeded in negotiating a peace treaty on favorable terms.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] It is possible that the Roman emperor Nero planned another attempt to conquer Kush before his death in AD 68.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Nero sent two centurions upriver as far as Bahr el Ghazal River in 66 AD in an attempt to discover the source of the Nile, per Seneca, or plan an attack, per Pliny.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Kush began to weaken by the third AD, Due mainly to succession problems and Rebellions.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] However, evidence of third century AD Kushite Kings at Philae in demotic and inscription shows that kush still make maintened it's full territory by the late 3rd century AD.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] It has been suggested that the Kushites reoccupied very southern part of Egypt after Roman forces were withdrawn to Aswan.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Kushite activities led others to Kushite control of that area (as far north as Philae) form the middle of the third century AD Until it's disintegration in 350 AD.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The fall of kush is often associated with a war with the Axumites.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] An Aksumite breif control of Meroe is confirmed by two fragmentary Greek inscriptions.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The better preserved one referred to a military battleand the imposition of a tribute.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] They probably belonged to Aksumite victory monuments and were dedicated to Maher, the god of war.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Thus, they must have been erected before Aksum's conversion to Christianity in around 340, probably by king Ousanas (r. c.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] An inscription from Aksum mentioning Kush as tributary kingdom may also be attributed to Ousanas.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] The trilingual stele of his successor Ezana describes another war which happened after 340.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Ezana's army followed the course of the Atbara until reaching the Nile confluence, where a battle was fought against Rebellious Kush.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Meroe itself is not mentioned, suggesting that Ezana did not attack the City.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Aksum's presence in kush was short-lived.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Meroitic texts from as early as the 1st century BC hint to subjugation of the Noba, who lived west of the Nile and were governed by their own chiefs and kings and were subjects to kush.
[src:kingdom-of-kush/kingdom-of-kush] Perhaps it was the increasingly arid climate that forced them to migrate to the Nile Valley, although they would not manage to Rebel and break through until the 4th century.
